{"title_page": "Fabrice Luchini", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Fabrice Luchini\n| image                 = Fabrice Luchini Cannes 2016.jpg\n| caption               = Luchini at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]]\n| birthname             = Robert Luchini\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1951|11|1}}\n| birth_place           = [[Paris]], France\n| othername             = \n| occupation            = [[Actor]]\n| years_active          = 1969\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Fabrice Luchini''' ({{IPA-fr|fab\u0281is lykini}}; born '''Robert Luchini'''; 1 November 1951) is a French stage and film actor. He has appeared in films such as ''[[Potiche]]'', ''[[The Women on the 6th Floor]]'', and ''[[In the House (film)|In the House]]''.\n\nFor his role in the 2015 film ''[[Courted (film)|Courted]]'' he won the [[Volpi Cup for Best Actor]] at the [[72nd Venice International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"winners\">{{cite web|title=LIVE: The winners of the 72nd Venice Film Festival|url=http://cineuropa.org/nw.aspx?t=newsdetail&did=298479|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nFabrice Luchini was born in Paris, into an Italian immigrant family from [[Assisi]]<ref>{{cite web|language=it |url=http://www.lexpress.fr/culture/scene/l-enigme-luchini_498015.html |title=L'\u00e9nigme Luchini |accessdate=2015-05-27}}</ref> who were greengrocers. He grew up around the neighbourhood of [[Goutte d'Or]] in Paris's [[18th arrondissement]]. When he was 13, his mother apprenticed him to a hairdresser in a trendy parlour in Avenue Matignon, where he would take the name of the hairdresser's son, Fabrice, in place of his real name, Robert. His first film role was in ''Tout peut arriver'' in 1969. He then appeared in [[\u00c9ric Rohmer]]'s ''[[Le Genou de Claire]]'' in 1970 playing a small role as an adolescent. He went on to appear in Rohmer's  ''[[Perceval le Gallois]]'' and ''[[Les Nuits de la pleine lune]]'', and also in films directed by [[Nagisa Oshima]], Pierre Zucca, [[Claude Lelouch]], [[Cedric Klapisch]] and [[\u00c9douard Molinaro]]. In 1990 he appeared in [[Christian Vincent (director)|Christian Vincent]]'s ''[[La Discr\u00e8te]]''.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=27em}}\n* ''[[Tout peut arriver]]'' (1969) - Fabrice\n* ''[[Claire's Knee|Le genou de Claire]]'' (1970) - Vincent\n* ''[[Valparaiso, Valparaiso]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[Immoral Tales (film)|Contes immoraux]]'' (1973) - Andr\u00e9 / Julie's cousin - Story 1\n* ''[[Vincent mit l'\u00e2ne dans un pr\u00e9 (et s'en vint dans l'autre)]]'' (1975) - Vincent Vergne\n* ''[[Ne (film)|Ne]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Les \u00e9crans d\u00e9chir\u00e9s]]'' (1976, Short) - Fabrice\n* ''[[Violette Nozi\u00e8re]]'' (1978) - Camus, l'\u00e9tudiant\n* ''[[Perceval le Gallois]]'' (1978) - [[Percival|Perceval]]\n* ''[[M\u00eame les m\u00f4mes ont du vague \u00e0 l'\u00e2me]]'' (1980) - Arthur\n* ''[[La femme de l'aviateur]]'' (1981) - Mercillat\n* ''[[La for\u00eat d\u00e9senchant\u00e9e]]'' (1981, Short)\n* ''[[T'es folle ou quoi?]]'' (1982) - Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Sevran\n* ''[[Jimmy Jazz (film)|Jimmy Jazz]]'' (1982, Short) - Fabrice\n* ''[[Zig Zag Story]]'' (1983) - Bob Hemler\n* ''[[Il ne faut jurer de rien]]'' (1983, Short)\n* ''[[Lettre de la Sierra Morena]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Emmanuelle 4]]'' (1984) - Oswaldo\n* ''[[Full Moon in Paris|Les nuits de la pleine lune]]'' (1984) - Octave\n* ''[[Rouge-gorge]]'' (1985) - Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric\n* ''[[Profs (1985 film)|Profs]]'' (1985) - Michel\n* ''[[Family Business (1986 film)|Conseil de famille]]'' (1986) - The shady lawyer\n* ''[[Max mon amour]]'' (1986) - Nicolas\n* ''[[Triple sec (film)|Triple sec]]'' (1986, Short)\n* ''[[Four Adventures of Reinette and Mirabelle|4 aventures de Reinette et Mirabelle]]'' (1987) - Painting Salesman\n* ''[[H\u00f4tel du Paradis|H\u00f4tel du paradis]]'' (1987) - Arthur\n* ''[[Les oreilles entre les dents]]'' (1987) - Luc Fabri\n* ''[[Alouette, je te plumerai]]'' (1988) - Jacques\n* ''[[La Couleur du vent]]'' (1988) - Serge\n* ''[[La discr\u00e8te]]'' (1990) - Antoine\n* ''[[Uranus (film)|Uranus]]'' (1990) - Jourdan\n* ''[[The Return of Casanova|Le retour de Casanova]]'' (1992) - Camille\n* ''[[Riens du tout]]'' (1992) - Lepetit\n* ''[[L'Arbre, le maire et la m\u00e9diath\u00e8que]]'' (1993) - Marc Rossignol - the School Teacher\n* ''[[Toxic Affair]]'' (1993) - The Analyst\n* ''[[Tout \u00e7a... pour \u00e7a !]]'' (1993) - Fabrice Lenormand\n* ''[[Colonel Chabert (1994 film)|Le Colonel Chabert]]'' (1994) - Derville\n* ''[[L'ann\u00e9e Juliette]]'' (1995) - Camille Prader\n* ''[[Beaumarchais (film)|Beaumarchais, l'insolent]]'' (1996) - [[Pierre-Augustin Caron de Beaumarchais]]\n* ''[[Men, Women: A User's Manual|Hommes, femmes, mode d'emploi]]'' (1996) - Fabio Lini\n* ''[[An Air So Pure]]'' (1997) - Magnus\n* ''[[On Guard (1997 film)|Le Bossu]]'' (1997) - Gonzague\n* ''[[Rien sur Robert]]'' (1999) - Didier Temple\n* ''[[No Scandal|Pas de scandale]]'' (1999) - Gr\u00e9goire Jeancourt\n* ''[[Barnie et ses petites contrari\u00e9t\u00e9s]]'' (2001) - Barnie\n* ''[[Le co\u00fbt de la vie]]'' (2003) - Brett\n* ''[[Intimate Strangers (2004 film)|Confidences trop intimes]]'' (aka ''Intimate Strangers'') (2004) - William\n* ''[[La cloche a sonn\u00e9]]'' (2005) - Simon Arcos\n* ''[[Jean-Philippe (film)|Jean-Philippe]]'' (2006) - Fabrice\n* ''[[Moli\u00e8re (2007 film)|Moli\u00e8re]]'' (2007) - M. Jourdain\n* ''[[Paris (2008 film)|Paris]]'' (2008) - Roland Verneuil\n* ''[[La fille de Monaco]]'' (2008) - Bertrand Beauvois\n* ''[[Mus\u00e9e haut, mus\u00e9e bas]]'' (2008) - Un gardien mus\u00e9e Malraux\n* ''[[My Father's Guests]]'' (2010) - Arnaud Paumelle\n* ''[[Potiche]]'' (2010) - Robert Pujol\n* ''[[The Women on the 6th Floor|Les femmes du 6\u00e8me \u00e9tage]]'' (2010) - Jean-Louis Joubert\n* ''[[In the House (film)|In the House]]'' (2012) - Germain Germain\n* ''[[Asterix and Obelix: God Save Britannia]]'' (2012) - [[Julius Caesar|Jules C\u00e9sar]]\n* ''[[Alceste \u00e0 bicyclette]]'' (2013) - Serge Tanneur\n* ''[[Gemma Bovery (film)|Gemma Bovery]]'' (2014) - Martin Joubert\n* ''Un d\u00e9but prometteur'' (2015) - Francis Vauvel\n* ''[[L'Hermine]]'' (2015) - Michel Racine\n* ''[[Slack Bay]]'' (2016) - Andr\u00e9 Van Peteghem\n* ''Un homme press\u00e9'' (2018) - Alain Wapler\n* ''L'empereur de Paris'' (2018) - Fouch\u00e9\n* ''[[The Mystery of Henri Pick]]'' (2019) - Jean-Michel Rouche\n* ''[[Joan of Arc (2019 film)|Joan of Arc]]'' (2019) - [[Charles VII of France|King of France]]\n* ''[[Alice and the Mayor]]'' (2019) - Paul Th\u00e9raneau\n* ''Le meilleur reste \u00e0 venir'' (2019) - Arthur\n{{div col end}}\n\n;Television\n* ''La cha\u00eene'' (TV movie by [[Claude Santelli]]) \u2013 Laurent (1979)\n* ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Fant\u00f4mas (1980 TV film)|fr|3=Fant\u00f4mas (mini-s\u00e9rie)|lt=Fant\u00f4mas}}'' (TV mini-series) \u2013 Bonardin (1980)\n:* \"L'\u00e9treinte du diable\" ([[Juan Luis Bu\u00f1uel]])\n:* \"L'\u00e9chafaud magique\" ([[Claude Chabrol]])\n* ''Le beau monde'' (TV movie by Michel Polac) \u2013 Jean-Pierre Davin (1981)\n* ''[[S\u00e9rie noire (TV series)|S\u00e9rie noire]]'' (TV series)\n:* \"Adieu la vie\" (Maurice Dugowson) \u2013 Kowal (1986)\n:* \"La f\u00e9e carabine\" ([[Yves Boisset]]) \u2013 Pastor (1988)\n* ''Tous en bo\u00eete'' (TV mini-series by Charles Nem\u00e8s) \u2013 Minimax (1986)\n* ''Les dossiers de l'\u00e9cran'' (TV series)\n:* ''L'argent du mur'' (TV movie by [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Delassus]]) \u2013 Bernd (1988)\n* ''Au nom du peuple fran\u00e7ais'' ([[Maurice Dugowson]]) \u2013 [[Robespierre]] (1988)\n* ''Les nuits r\u00e9volutionnaires'' (TV mini-series by Charles Brabant) \u2013 Huguenot sans-culotte (1989)\n* ''Six crimes sans assassin'' (TV movie by [[Bernard Stora]]) \u2013 Simon Lampias (1990)\n* ''[[Call My Agent !]]'' (TV Series / 1 Episode) - Himself (2017)\n\n==Theatre==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''[[En attendant Godot]]'' (1978)\n*''Tro\u00eflus et Cressida'' (1979)\n*''De toutes les couleurs'' (1982)\n*''Voyage au bout de la nuit'' (1986)\n*''Le Veilleur de nuit'' (1986)\n*''La Valse du hasard'' (1986)\n*''Le Secret'' (1987)\n*''Voyage au bout de la nuit'' (1987)\n*''Voyage au bout de la nuit'' (1988)\n*''Une folie \u00e9lectrique'' (1989)\n*''Deux femmes pour un fant\u00f4me'' and ''La Baby-sitter'' (1990)\n*''La Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de chasse'' (1991)\n*''Partenaires'' (1993)\n*''\u00ab Art \u00bb'' (1994)\n*''Fabrice Luchini dit des textes de [[Baudelaire]], [[Victor Hugo|Hugo]], [[Jean de La Fontaine|La Fontaine]], [[Nietzsche]]'' (1996)\n*''Un c\u0153ur simple'' (1996)\n*''L\u2019Arriv\u00e9e \u00e0 New-York'' (2000)\n*''\u00c9coute mon ami (et autres textes de [[Louis Jouvet]])'' (2002)\n*''Knock ou le triomphe de la m\u00e9decine'' (2002)\n*''Fabrice Luchini dit des textes de [[Jean de La Fontaine|La Fontaine]], [[Nietzsche]], [[Louis-Ferdinand C\u00e9line|C\u00e9line]], [[Baudelaire]]'' (2005)\n*''Molly'' (2005) \n*''Le Point sur Robert'' (2006, 2007, 2008, 2009)\n*''Fabrice Luchini lit [[Philippe Muray]]'' (2010, 2011, 2012)\n*''La Fontaine'' (2011) \n*''Une heure de tranquillit\u00e9'' (2013)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Literature==\n*In 2010, Fabrice Luchini wrote the preface of two books: ''A la rencontre de Sacha Guitry'', published by Editions Oxus, and ''Seul avec tous'' by Laurent Terzieff, published by Presses de la Renaissance.\n*In 2011, he collaborated in a book by Philippe Muray, published by les Cahiers d'histoire de la philosophie (Editions du Cerf). \n*Also in 2011, he released ''Fabrice Luchini lit fragments d'un discours amoureux'' through Audiolib.\n*In 2012, he released ''Variations (La Fontaine & Baudelaire)'' on CD and DVD on Barclay / Universal Music France\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n*[[Prix Jean Gabin]] (1991)\n*[[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actor]], for ''[[Tout \u00e7a... pour \u00e7a !]]'' (1994)\n*[[Prix du Brigadier]] (2002)\n*Silver George for Best Actor at the [[29th Moscow International Film Festival]] (2007)<ref name=\"Moscow2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2007 |title=29th Moscow International Film Festival (2007) |access-date=2013-05-30 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421051129/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=2007 |archive-date=21 April 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Fabrice Luchini}}\n* {{IMDb name|name=Fabrice Luchini|id=0524528}}\n\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{Volpi Cup for Best Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luchini, Fabrice}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male film actors]]\n[[Category:French male stage actors]]\n[[Category:French people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century French male actors]]\n[[Category:French male television actors]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Volpi Cup for Best Actor winners]]\n[[Category:Volpi Cup winners]]\n[[Category:People of Umbrian descent]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Laureates of the prix du Brigadier]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Fabrice Luchini\n| image                 = Fabrice Luchini Cannes 2016.jpg\n| caption               = Luchini at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]]\n| birthname             = Robert Luchini\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1951|11|1}}\n| birth_place           = [[Paris]], France\n| othername             = \n| occupation            = [[Actor]]\n| years_active          = 1969\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Fabrice Luchini''' ({{IPA-fr|fab\u0281is lykini}}; born '''Robert Luchini'''; 1 November 1951) is a French stage and film actor. He has appeared in films such as ''[[Potiche]]'', ''[[The Women on the 6th Floor]]'', and ''[[In the House (film)|In the House]]''.\n\nFor his role in the 2015 film ''[[Courted (film)|Courted]]'' he won the [[Volpi Cup for Best Actor]] at the [[72nd Venice International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"winners\">{{cite web|title=LIVE: The winners of the 72nd Venice Film Festival|url=http://cineuropa.org/nw.aspx?t=newsdetail&did=298479|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nFabrice Luchini was born in Paris, into an Italian immigrant family from [[Assisi]]<ref>{{cite web|language=it |url=http://www.lexpress.fr/culture/scene/l-enigme-luchini_498015.html |title=L'\u00e9nigme Luchini |accessdate=2015-05-27}}</ref> who were greengrocers. He grew up around the neighbourhood of [[Goutte d'Or]] in Paris's [[18th arrondissement]]. When he was 13, his mother apprenticed him to a hairdresser in a trendy parlour in Avenue Matignon, where he would take the name of the hairdresser's son, Fabrice, in place of his real name, Robert. His first film role was in ''Tout peut arriver'' in 1969. He then appeared in [[\u00c9ric Rohmer]]'s ''[[Le Genou de Claire]]'' in 1970 playing a small role as an adolescent. He went on to appear in Rohmer's  ''[[Perceval le Gallois]]'' and ''[[Les Nuits de la pleine lune]]'', and also in films directed by [[Nagisa Oshima]], Pierre Zucca, [[Claude Lelouch]], [[Cedric Klapisch]] and [[\u00c9douard Molinaro]]. In 1990 he appeared in [[Christian Vincent (director)|Christian Vincent]]'s ''[[La Discr\u00e8te]]''.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=27em}}\n* ''[[Tout peut arriver]]'' (1969) - Fabrice\n* ''[[Claire's Knee|Le genou de Claire]]'' (1970) - Vincent\n* ''[[Valparaiso, Valparaiso]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[Immoral Tales (film)|Contes immoraux]]'' (1973) - Andr\u00e9 / Julie's cousin - Story 1\n* ''[[Vincent mit l'\u00e2ne dans un pr\u00e9 (et s'en vint dans l'autre)]]'' (1975) - Vincent Vergne\n* ''[[Ne (film)|Ne]]'' (1975)\n* ''[[Les \u00e9crans d\u00e9chir\u00e9s]]'' (1976, Short) - Fabrice\n* ''[[Violette Nozi\u00e8re]]'' (1978) - Camus, l'\u00e9tudiant\n* ''[[Perceval le Gallois]]'' (1978) - [[Percival|Perceval]]\n* ''[[M\u00eame les m\u00f4mes ont du vague \u00e0 l'\u00e2me]]'' (1980) - Arthur\n* ''[[La femme de l'aviateur]]'' (1981) - Mercillat\n* ''[[La for\u00eat d\u00e9senchant\u00e9e]]'' (1981, Short)\n* ''[[T'es folle ou quoi?]]'' (1982) - Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Sevran\n* ''[[Jimmy Jazz (film)|Jimmy Jazz]]'' (1982, Short) - Fabrice\n* ''[[Zig Zag Story]]'' (1983) - Bob Hemler\n* ''[[Il ne faut jurer de rien]]'' (1983, Short)\n* ''[[Lettre de la Sierra Morena]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Emmanuelle 4]]'' (1984) - Oswaldo\n* ''[[Full Moon in Paris|Les nuits de la pleine lune]]'' (1984) - Octave\n* ''[[Rouge-gorge]]'' (1985) - Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric\n* ''[[Profs (1985 film)|Profs]]'' (1985) - Michel\n* ''[[Family Business (1986 film)|Conseil de famille]]'' (1986) - The shady lawyer\n* ''[[Max mon amour]]'' (1986) - Nicolas\n* ''[[Triple sec (film)|Triple sec]]'' (1986, Short)\n* ''[[Four Adventures of Reinette and Mirabelle|4 aventures de Reinette et Mirabelle]]'' (1987) - Painting Salesman\n* ''[[H\u00f4tel du Paradis|H\u00f4tel du paradis]]'' (1987) - Arthur\n* ''[[Les oreilles entre les dents]]'' (1987) - Luc Fabri\n* ''[[Alouette, je te plumerai]]'' (1988) - Jacques\n* ''[[La Couleur du vent]]'' (1988) - Serge\n* ''[[La discr\u00e8te]]'' (1990) - Antoine\n* ''[[Uranus (film)|Uranus]]'' (1990) - Jourdan\n* ''[[The Return of Casanova|Le retour de Casanova]]'' (1992) - Camille\n* ''[[Riens du tout]]'' (1992) - Lepetit\n* ''[[L'Arbre, le maire et la m\u00e9diath\u00e8que]]'' (1993) - Marc Rossignol - the School Teacher\n* ''[[Toxic Affair]]'' (1993) - The Analyst\n* ''[[Tout \u00e7a... pour \u00e7a !]]'' (1993) - Fabrice Lenormand\n* ''[[Colonel Chabert (1994 film)|Le Colonel Chabert]]'' (1994) - Derville\n* ''[[L'ann\u00e9e Juliette]]'' (1995) - Camille Prader\n* ''[[Beaumarchais (film)|Beaumarchais, l'insolent]]'' (1996) - [