{"title_page": "Tzu Chi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox monastery\n| image          =File:Tzu Chi Logo.jpg\n| caption        = Tzu Chi's [[Nelumbo nucifera|lotus]] Logo.\n| name           = Tzu Chi Foundation\n| full           = Buddhist Compassion Relief Tzu Chi Foundation, Taiwan\n| native_name    = \u6148\u6fdf\u57fa\u91d1\u6703\n| native_name_lang = zh\n| established    = 1966\n| order          = [[Mahayana]]\n| founder        = [[Cheng Yen]]\n| abbot          = [[Cheng Yen]]\n| location       = [[Hualien City|Hualien]], [[Taiwan]]\n| coord          = \n| public_access  = \n| other_info     = \n|website={{url|http://tw.tzuchi.org/en}}}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| t       = \u8ca1\u5718\u6cd5\u4eba\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u4f5b\u654e\u6148\u6fdf\u6148\u5584\u4e8b\u696d\u57fa\u91d1\u6703\n| s       = \u8d22\u56e2\u6cd5\u4eba\u4e2d\u534e\u6c11\u56fd\u4f5b\u654e\u6148\u6d4e\u6148\u5584\u4e8b\u4e1a\u57fa\u91d1\u4f1a\n| bpmf    = \u3118\u311e\u02ca\u310a\u3128\u3122\u02ca\u3108\u311a\u02c7\u3116\u3123\u02ca\u3113\u3128\u3125 \u310f\u3128\u311a\u02ca\u3107\u3127\u3123\u02ca\u310d\u3128\u311b\u02ca\u3108\u311b\u02ca\u3110\u3127\u3120\u02cb\u3118\u02ca\u3110\u3127\u02cb\u3118\u02ca\u3115\u3122\u02cb\u3115\u02cb\u3127\u311d\u02cb\u3110\u3127 \u3110\u3127\u3123 \u310f\u3128\u311f\u02cb\n| p       = C\u00e1itu\u00e1n F\u01cer\u00e9n Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 M\u00edngu\u00f3 F\u00f3ji\u00e0o C\u00ed J\u00ec C\u00edsh\u00e0n Sh\u00ecy\u00e8 J\u012bj\u012bn Hu\u00ec\n| altname = Short name\n| t2      = \u6148\u6fdf\u57fa\u91d1\u6703\n| s2      = \u6148\u6d4e\u57fa\u91d1\u4f1a\n| p2      = C\u00ed j\u00ec j\u012bj\u012bn hu\u00ec\n| poj2    = Ch\u00fb-ch\u00e8 ki-kim-h\u014de\n}}\n{{buddhism}}\n\n'''Buddhist Compassion Relief Tzu Chi Foundation, Republic of China''', known for short as the '''Tzu Chi Foundation''' ({{lang-zh|t=\u6148\u6fdf\u57fa\u91d1\u6703|p=C\u00ed J\u00ec j\u012bj\u012bn hu\u00ec|l=\"Compassionate Relief Foundation\"}}), is a [[Taiwan]]ese international humanitarian and [[non-governmental organization]] (NGO). The foundation has several sub-organizations such as the Tzu Chi International Medical Association (TIMA) and also the Tzu Chi Collegiate Youth Association (Tzu Ching) ({{zh|t=\u6148\u6fdf\u5927\u5c08\u9751\u5e74\u806f\u8abc\u6703 (\u6148\u9751))}}. Tzu Chi volunteers and relief workers are mostly recognizable by their blue and white uniforms called, in {{zh|t=\u85cd\u5929\u767d\u96f2}}, ''l\u00e1nti\u0101n b\u00e1iy\u00fan'', ( lit. 'blue sky, white clouds'). The foundation's work includes medical aid, disaster relief, and environmental work such as recycling. It is operated by a worldwide network of volunteers and employees and has been awarded a special consultative status at the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]].<ref>O'Neill, Mark (2010), ''[http://www.books.com.tw/exep/assp.php/jamezku/products/F012089631 Tzu Chi: Serving With Compassion]'', John Wiley & Sons</ref> \n\nThe Tzu Chi Foundation was founded by Master [[Cheng Yen]], a Taiwanese Buddhist nun, or ''[[bhikkhuni]]'', in 1966 as a Buddhist humanitarian organization. The organization began as a group of thirty housewives who saved money for needy families. Tzu Chi gradually expanded its services over time, opening a free medical clinic in 1972 and building its first hospital in 1986. The organization underwent a rapid expansion in the late 1980s and early 1990s, coinciding with a surge of popularity in [[Humanistic Buddhism]] in Taiwan. In the 1990s the organization started major international disaster relief efforts. Tzu Chi is known for undertaking long term projects such as building new homes, schools, hospitals, and places of worship (including churches and mosques for non-Buddhists) for victims following a disaster. As of 2013, the organization was estimated at over 10 million members worldwide throughout 47 countries. \n\nTzu Chi has a policy of being secular in its humanitarian work, however [[Dharma (Buddhism)|Dharma]] teachings are often integrated into its practices for volunteers. Cheng Yen is considered to be one of the \"[[Four Heavenly Kings (Taiwan)|Four Heavenly Kings]]\" of Taiwanese Buddhism, and Tzu Chi itself is considered to be one of the \"[[Four Great Mountains (Taiwan)|Four Great Mountains]]\", or four major Buddhist organizations of Taiwan along with [[Fo Guang Shan]], [[Dharma Drum Mountain]], and [[Chung Tai Shan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://info.taiwan.net.tw/tourbusE/december_page1.html |title=Come to Taiwan, Return with good memories |publisher=Info.taiwan.net.tw |accessdate=2012-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227183910/http://info.taiwan.net.tw/tourbusE/december_page1.html |archivedate=27 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shuai|first=J. J.|last2=Chen|first2=H. C.|last3=Chang|first3=C. H.|date=2010-12-01|title=Visualization of the Taiwaness Buddhism web based on social network analysis|journal=2010 International Computer Symposium (ICS2010)|pages=187\u2013191|doi=10.1109/COMPSYM.2010.5685523|df=dmy-all|isbn=978-1-4244-7639-8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wvGWJcQ3ZX0C&dq=four+heavenly+kings+taiwan+tzu+chi&q=four+heavenly+kings+|title=2600 Years of Sambuddhatva: Global Journey of Awakening|date=2011-01-01|isbn=9789559349334|pages=282|language=en|access-date=4 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410133539/https://books.google.com/books?id=wvGWJcQ3ZX0C&dq=four+heavenly+kings+taiwan+tzu+chi&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=four+heavenly+kings+|archive-date=10 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n==History==\n\nThe Tzu Chi Foundation was founded as a charity organization with [[Buddhist]] origins by the Buddhist nun Master [[Cheng Yen]] in 1966 in [[Hualien City|Hualien]], Taiwan after Cheng Yen saw the humanitarian work of Christian missionaries in Taiwan in the [[Taiwan after World War II|post World War II period]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion|last=O'Neill|first=Mark|date=2010-05-17|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=19|language=en}}</ref> She was inspired by her master and mentor, the late Venerable Master [[Yin Shun]] (\u5370\u9806\u5c0e\u5e2b, Y\u00ecn Sh\u00f9n d\u01ceosh\u012b) a proponent of [[Humanistic Buddhism]], who exhorted her to \"work for Buddhism and for all sentient beings\". The organization began with a motto of \"instructing the rich and saving the poor\" as a group of thirty [[housewives]] who saved fifty [[New Taiwan dollar|cents]] ([[US$]]0.02) every day and stored them in bamboo savings banks to donate to needy families.<ref name=\"parabola\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parabola.org/the-desire-to-relieve-all-suffering|title=THE DESIRE TO RELIEVE ALL SUFFERING|date=2010|publisher=Parabola Magazine|last1=Wolkstein|first1=Diane|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923002225/http://www.parabola.org/the-desire-to-relieve-all-suffering|archivedate=23 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of Dharma Master Cheng Yen|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=159%3Aintroduction&catid=81%3Aabout&Itemid=198&lang=en|website=tw.tzuchi.org|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823142309/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=159%3Aintroduction&catid=81%3Aabout&Itemid=198&lang=en|archive-date=23 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTzu Chi experienced modest growth in the first two decades of its establishment, it grew to 293 members in 1968 and by 1986 had just 8,000 members.<ref name=\"chinaperspectives.revues.org\" /> The foundation gradually expanded its services since starting as a group of thirty housewives, raising money for disaster relief after a small fire in 1970 that destroyed 43 buildings and opening its first free medical clinic in 1972.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion|last=O'Neill|first=Mark|date=2010-05-17|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=22|language=en}}</ref> In 1986 the foundation established its first hospital in [[Hualien City]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nWith the surge in popularity of [[Humanistic Buddhism]] in Taiwan in the late 1980s and 1990s, and the publicity from fundraising to build its first hospital, Tzu Chi enjoyed a rapid expansion in membership alongside several other major Taiwanese Buddhist organizations during this time.<ref name=\":25\"/><ref name=\"chinaperspectives.revues.org\" /> From 1987 to 1991, Tzu Chi membership doubled in size each year, by 1994, it boasted a membership of 4 million members.<ref name=\"chinaperspectives.revues.org\">{{cite journal|last1=Schak|first1=David|last2=Hsiao|first2=Hsin-Huang Michael|title=Taiwan's Socially Engaged Buddhist Groups|journal=China Perspectives|volume=2005|date=2005|issue=59|df=dmy-all|doi=10.4000/chinaperspectives.2803}}</ref> Tzu Chi's expanded its aid work to the [[People's Republic of China]] in 1991, during the [[Eastern China flood of 1991|eastern China floods]].<ref name=\":5\" /> In 1993, the foundation created a bone marrow registry, an effort that eventually caused Taiwan to alter its bone marrow laws, and organized a nationwide volunteer program for Taiwan in 1996.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nThe foundation achieved much media attention in Taiwan in 2015 with a plan to develop a plot of land in [[Neihu District]] into a disaster relief center and cultural park which led to the destruction of parts of the Neihu conservation zone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/asoc/201503160028.aspx|title=City officials, Neihu residents welcome Tzu Chi's project pullback {{!}} Society {{!}} FOCUS TAIWAN - CNA ENGLISH NEWS|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref><ref name=\"taipeitimes.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2015/03/17/2003613729|title=Tzu Chi retracts controversial project - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2015/03/11/2003613258/1|title=Tzu Chi's Neihu land should be rejuvenated - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/local/taipei/2015/03/17/431281/City-officials.htm|title=City officials, Neihu residents welcome Tzu Chi retreat from project - The China Post|date=2015-04-14|access-date=2018-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414225114/http://chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/local/taipei/2015/03/17/431281/City-officials.htm|archive-date=14 April 2015}}</ref> The incident led to widespread critical coverage of Tzu Chi by the Taiwanese media, and scrutiny into its finances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2013/01/24/2003553308|title=Tzu Chi buildings spark protests - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref><ref name=\"taipeitimes.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chinapost.com.tw/editorial/taiwan-issues/2015/03/22/431650/Tzu-Chi.htm|title=Tzu Chi needs more transparency in charity work - The China Post|date=2015-03-24|access-date=2018-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324231306/http://chinapost.com.tw/editorial/taiwan-issues/2015/03/22/431650/Tzu-Chi.htm|archive-date=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?cid=1103&MainCatID=&id=20150319000091|title=Tzu Chi in Tainan school land rental subsidy controversy\uff5cWantChinaTimes.com|date=2015-04-14|access-date=2018-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414173534/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?cid=1103&MainCatID=&id=20150319000091|archive-date=14 April 2015}}</ref> During this time several [[Fake news|unsubstantiated reports]] circulated in Taiwan about the foundation, including unfounded claims that the foundation invested in tobacco and weapons companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20150322000132&cid=1701|title=Tzu Chi has admitted errors; it's time for compassion\uff5cWantChinaTimes.com|date=2015-04-14|access-date=2018-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414173530/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20150322000132&cid=1701|archive-date=14 April 2015}}</ref> Despite authorities not finding any illicit activity with its finances, calls for greater transparency were made.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20150303000052&cid=1103|title=Tzu Chi Foundation urged to publish detailed donation list|last=|first=|date=|work=Want China Times|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414173317/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20150303000052&cid=1103|archive-date=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nTzu Chi has grown to become a significant actor in civil society, Tzu Chi is not only the largest Buddhist organization in Taiwan,<ref name=\"chinaperspectives.revues.org2\">{{cite journal|last1=Schak|first1=David|last2=Hsiao|first2=Hsin-Huang Michael|date=2005|title=Taiwan's Socially Engaged Buddhist Groups|journal=China Perspectives|volume=2005|issue=59|df=dmy-all|doi=10.4000/chinaperspectives.2803}}</ref> but also Taiwan's largest owner of private land.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.taiwannews.com.tw/etn/news_content.php?id=2698712|title=Why Tzu Chi is sparking resentment|date=6 March 2016|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915192203/http://www.taiwannews.com.tw/etn/news_content.php?id=2698712|archive-date=15 September 2016|url-status=live|agency=Central News Agency|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of 2013, the organization was estimated to have approximately 10 million members worldwide, and chapters in 47 countries.<ref name=\":34\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzdyNvcRTWk|title=Master Cheng Yen and Tzu Chi|publisher=The Discovery Channel|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=293&Itemid=283&lang=en|title=Tzu Chi Missions|website=tw.tzuchi.org|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109072414/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=293&Itemid=283&lang=en|archive-date=9 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\n[[File:KL Tzu-Chi Jing Si Hall.jpg|thumb|Main hall at Tzu Chi Foundation]]\nThe four major causes of Tzu Chi are ''Charity'', ''Medicine'', ''Education'', and ''Humanity'', as highlighted by the official motto, or concept of \"Four endeavors, eight footprints\" ({{zh|t=\u56db\u5927\u5fd7\u696d\uff0c\u516b\u5927\u8173\u5370}}). The eight footprints are [[charity (practice)|charity]] causes, medical contributions, [[education]] development, humanities, international disaster assistance, bone-marrow donation, community volunteerism, and environmental protection.\n\nThe official website for the organization states that the organization started with Charity, and then extended its aims to include Medicine, Education and Culture. Its stated goal is to promote \"sincerity, integrity, trust, and honesty\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=293&Itemid=283&lang=en|title=Tzu Chi Missions|website=tw.tzuchi.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109072414/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=293&Itemid=283&lang=en|archive-date=9 November 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=15 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTzu Chi is notably distinct from the other [[Four Great Mountains (Taiwan)|Four Great Mountains]] in respect to three main unique characteristics. First of all, the founder of the organization is a female. Secondly, the founder is not a Buddhist scholar who promotes a specific interpretation of Buddhism nor started any kind of religious movement. And finally, the organization is officially a charitable organization and Tzu Chi itself focuses primarily on humanitarianism and community service rather than Buddhist spiritual development.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hsin-Huang Michael|first1=Hsiao|last2=Schak|first2=David|date=2005|title=Taiwan's Socially Engaged Buddhist Groups|url=https://chinaperspectives.revues.org/2803#tocto2n6|url-status=live|journal=China Perspectives|issue=59|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815194230/http://chinaperspectives.revues.org/2803#tocto2n6|archive-date=15 August 2016|accessdate=12 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Logo===\n\nConsisting of a ship that also simultaneously bears the lotus fruit and flower, the Tzu Chi logo symbolizes that the world can be made a better place by planting good karmic seeds. Followers believe that these seeds are required for flowers bloom and bear fruit, which is a metaphor for their beliefs that a better society can be created with good actions and pure thoughts. The ship represents Tzu Chi steering a ship of compassion, representing their goal in saving all beings that suffer, while the Eight Petals represent the [[Noble Eightfold Path]] in [[Buddhism]], which Tzu Chi uses as their guide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tzuchi.us/blog/tzu-chi-logo/|title=Tzu Chi Logo - Tzu Chi USA|website=www.tzuchi.us|access-date=2017-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709005113/https://www.tzuchi.us/blog/tzu-chi-logo/|archive-date=9 July 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Noble Eightfold Path consists of:\n# [[View (Buddhism)|Right View]]\n# [[Noble Eightfold Path#Right resolve|Right Thought]]\n# [[Noble Eightfold Path#Right speech|Right Speech]]\n# [[Noble Eightfold Path#Right action|Right Action]]\n# [[Noble Eightfold Path#Right livelihood|Right Livelihood]]\n# [[Noble Eightfold Path#Right effort|Right Effort]]\n# [[Sati (Buddhism)|Right Mindfulness]]\n# [[Right concentration|Right Focus]]\n\n===Tzu Chi's Ten Precepts===\n[[File:The Great Awakened of the Universe (\u5b87\u5b99\u5927\u89ba\u8457) is the depiction of Buddha of Tzu Chi Foundation. In the statue, Buddha is letting the world witness his enlightenment.jpg|thumb|Tzu Chi Foundation's depiction of the Buddha on a wall mural. The image is known as \"The Great Awakened of the Universe (\u5b87\u5b99\u5927\u89ba\u8457)\".]]Tzu Chi also has its own customized version of the [[Five Precepts|Buddhist Precepts]] as formulated by Master Cheng-Yen. The Ten Precepts of Tzu Chi are:\n\n#No killing\n# No stealing\n# No fornication\n# No lying\n# No drinking\n# No smoking or use of narcotics or [[betel nuts]]\n# No gambling\n# Practice [[filial piety]] and develop pleasant manners and speech\n# Abide by traffic laws\n# No participation in political activities or demonstrations\n\nMaster Cheng-Yen has stated that she developed these rules based on the new needs of modern society.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Ten Precepts of Tzu Chi|url=http://www.tzuchi.net/TCSC.nsf/0adbb3db1b96266f48256ae00021f8ae/9991505677819b0b48256ae8006b85c2|website=tzuchi.net|accessdate=3 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911071105/http://www.tzuchi.net/TCSC.nsf/0adbb3db1b96266f48256ae00021f8ae/9991505677819b0b48256ae8006b85c2|archive-date=11 September 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Medical Mission ==\nOne of the first major initiatives Tzu Chi took part in was the \"Tzu Chi Medical Mission\". This effort was inspired in 1970 after Cheng Yen noticed a link between poverty and illness after spending six years among the poor of eastern Taiwan.\n\nTzu Chi's first medical outreach occurred in 1972 when a free clinic was opened in [[Hualien City|Hualien]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://olbios.org/life-of-the-mother-teresa-of-asia/|title=Life of the \"Mother Teresa of Asia\" {{!}} Olbios|date=2016-01-26|work=Olbios|access-date=2017-03-18|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319115145/http://olbios.org/life-of-the-mother-teresa-of-asia/|archive-date=19 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Tzu Chi Hospital ===\n[[File:Hualien Tzu Chi General Hospital.JPG|thumb|Tzu Chi General Hospital in Hualien in 2011]]\nThe Foundation established its first Tzu Chi Hospital in [[Hualien City|Hualien]] in 1986. A 600-bed general hospital had been planned in 1979 to service the impoverished eastern coast of Taiwan.  A primary concern for Cheng Yen was that the area was isolated and the people in the area were cut off from aid during disasters.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC&dq=Tzu+Chi:+Serving+with+Compassion.|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion.|last=Mark.|first=O'Neill|date=2010-01-01|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=26|oclc=940634655}}</ref> Despite setbacks both in funding for the hospital and finding an acceptable site. Ground was broken on the site eventually chosen on 5 February 1983 at a ceremony officiated by then Provincial Governor (later President) [[Lee Teng-Hui]]. However, two weeks after ground was broken, Cheng Yen received a notice from the military telling her that the property was needed by the military and that construction would have to stop.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.tzuchi.com.tw/en/index.php/history/7-hualien-tzu-chi-hospital|title=Hualien Tzu Chi Hospital|access-date=2017-03-19|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052400/http://www.tzuchi.com.tw/en/index.php/history/7-hualien-tzu-chi-hospital|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XtDRTLTwD88C&dq=The+Life+and+Teachings+of+Venerable+Master+Cheng+Yen|title=Challenges The Life and Teachings of Venerable Master Cheng Yen|last=Gary|first=Ho|date=2014-01-01|publisher=Harbour Publishing|isbn=9781553659921|location=|pages=44|oclc=957463283}}</ref>\n\nA new site was obtained for the hospital with help from Minister of the Interior Lin Yang-kang.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC&dq=Tzu+Chi:+Serving+with+Compassion.|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion.|last=Mark.|first=O'Neill|date=2010-01-01|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=28|oclc=940634655}}</ref>  A second groundbreaking occurred on 2 April 1984 at the new site.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eng.tzuchi.my/index.php/culture/culture-news-k2/item/7498-50-years-of-tzu-chi-looking-back-and-striding-forward|title=50 Years of Tzu Chi: Looking Back and Striding Forward|access-date=2017-03-19|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052417/http://eng.tzuchi.my/index.php/culture/culture-news-k2/item/7498-50-years-of-tzu-chi-looking-back-and-striding-forward|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The publicity of the project to build the hospital led to a significant increase in the number of Tzu Chi volunteers, with Tzu Chi membership increasing six-fold by the time of the second groundbreaking since the announcement of the project in 1979.<ref name=\":25\"/> Construction was completed and the hospital opened on 17 August 1986.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nTzu Chi has since built hospitals in [[Yuli, Hualien|Yuli]], Hualien County; [[Dalin, Chiayi|Dalin]], [[Jiayi County]]; [[Guanshan, Taitung|Guanshan]], [[Taidong County]];  [[Tanzi District]], [[Taichung City]]; and [[Xindian District|Xindian]], [[New Taipei City]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=W4PuparQrsUC&pg=PA94&dq=tzu+chi+hospitals+yuli#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20hospitals%20yuli&f=false|title=The Politics of Buddhist Organizations in Taiwan, 1989-2003: Safeguard the Faith, Build a Pure Land, Help the Poor|last=Lalibert\u00e9|first=Andr\u00e9|date=2013-08-21|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134353545|location=|pages=94|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://app.tzuchi.com.tw/tzuchi_en/About_TP_Center/Default.htm|title=About Medicine Mission|last=|first=|date=|website=Buddhist Tzu Chi General Hospital|access-date=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to building hospitals the [[Tzu Chi College of Nursing]] was founded on 17 September 1989 in Hualien in order to address the shortage of nurses on Taiwan's east coast, with a focus on serving the poor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tzuchimedicalfoundation.org/about-tzu-chi/tzu-chi-missions/|title=Tzu Chi Missions|date=2014-12-03|work=BUDDHIST TZU CHI MEDICAL FOUNDATION|access-date=2017-04-29|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170429025148/http://www.tzuchimedicalfoundation.org/about-tzu-chi/tzu-chi-missions/|archive-date=29 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4dlOAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA127&dq=tzu+chi+nursing+college#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20nursing%20college&f=false|title=Ecofeminism and Globalization: Exploring Culture, Context, and Religion|last=Eaton|last2=Lorentzen|date=2004-09-08|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=9780585482767|location=|pages=127|language=en}}</ref> It was the first private nursing college in Taiwan to waive tuition for selected courses, in addition to providing full scholarships for qualified [[Taiwan aborigine]] students.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n=== Bone Marrow registry ===\n[[File:The Buddist Tzu Chi University.JPG|thumb|Main building at [[Tzu Chi University]]]]\nTzu Chi created a [[bone marrow]] registry, the Tzu Chi Bone Marrow Bank, in 1993 after a young follower of Cheng Yen was diagnosed with Leukemia.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XtDRTLTwD88C&pg=PA164&dq=tzu+chi+bone+marrow#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20bone%20marrow&f=false|title=Challenges: The Life and Teachings of Venerable Master Cheng Yen|last=Gary|date=2012-03-23|publisher=D & M Publishers|isbn=9781553659921|location=|pages=163|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":33\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC&pg=PA145&dq=tzu+chi+bone+marrow#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20bone%20marrow&f=false|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion|last=O'Neill|first=Mark|date=2010-05-17|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=145|language=en}}</ref>  Cheng Yen referred to the concept of bone marrow donation as a way to \"save a life without harming yourself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tzuchi.ca/index.php/en/about-us/tzu-chi-foundation|title=Tzu Chi Foundation|last=\u6148\u6fdf\u57fa\u91d1\u6703|access-date=2017-04-02|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402170105/http://www.tzuchi.ca/index.php/en/about-us/tzu-chi-foundation|archive-date=2 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This effort to register bone marrow donors from an organization with such massive membership like Tzu Chi caused Taiwan to change its laws regarding organ donations.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC&pg=PA145&dq=tzu+chi+bone+marrow#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20bone%20marrow&f=false|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion|last=O'Neill|first=Mark|date=2010-05-17|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=146|language=en}}</ref>{{refn|Prior to 1993 Taiwanese law only allowed organ transplants between relatives.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC&pg=PA145&dq=tzu+chi+bone+marrow#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20bone%20marrow&f=false|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion|last=O'Neill|first=Mark|date=2010-05-17|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=146|language=en}}</ref>|group=note}} This registry became a division of the new Tzu Chi Stem Cells Center, which was founded to improve research and treatment capabilities.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=26vBBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA17&dq=Tzu+Chi+Stem+Cells+Center#v=onepage&q=Tzu%20Chi%20Stem%20Cells%20Center&f=false|title=Hematopoietic Cell Transplantation in Children with Cancer|last=Smith|first=Franklin O.|last2=Reaman|first2=Gregory H.|last3=Racadio|first3=Judy M.|date=2013-11-26|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9783642399206|location=|pages=17|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":33\"/> By 2007 the program had saved the lives of almost 1,500 people in 25 different countries.<ref name=\":33\" /> By 2008, Tzu Chi had registered more than 307,657 bone marrow donors.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XtDRTLTwD88C&pg=PA164&dq=tzu+chi+bone+marrow#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20bone%20marrow&f=false|title=Challenges: The Life and Teachings of Venerable Master Cheng Yen|last=Gary|date=2012-03-23|publisher=D & M Publishers|isbn=9781553659921|location=|pages=165|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== College of Medicine ===\nTzu Chi established the [[Tzu Chi College of Medicine]] in 1994.  This college became [[Tzu Chi University]] in 2000. In the meantime Cheng-Yen appealed to the Taiwanese public to donate their bodies for medical training, attempting to dispel traditional taboos in the process. As a result of this appeal, public support for [[body donation]]s surged nationwide. Consequently, at the Tzu Chi College of Medicine, there is one body for every four students to study as opposed to one body for every two hundred students at one school, the ratio is the lowest in the country.\n\nIn 1995, the Athletic Drug Testing Center was established at the request of the Ministry of Education and went into operation in 1996 during a national sporting event when gold medal winners were tested for banned drugs.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n== Disaster relief ==\n[[File:Tzu Chi Culture and Communication Foundation 20080309.jpg|thumb|Tzu Chi Culture and Communications building]]\nTzu Chi is most well known for its disaster relief efforts worldwide. In carrying out these projects, Tzu Chi has a policy that forbids public gatherings for the sole purpose of specific political, economic, and religious groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.us.tzuchi.org/usa/images/other/TzuChiFAQ-global.pdf|title=Frequently Asked Questions about Tzu Chi|last=|first=|date=2011-07-25|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725233133/http://www.us.tzuchi.org/usa/images/other/TzuChiFAQ-global.pdf|archive-date=25 July 2011|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> Tzu Chi volunteers are not to discuss business, politics, or preach religion while giving aid.<ref name=\":25\"/> One of the most iconic attributes of Tzu Chi disaster relief efforts is that volunteers not only provide short term aid but also partake in long term projects to rebuild the communities affected. Tzu Chi often builds new homes, schools, hospitals, and places of worship (including churches and mosques for non-Buddhists) for victims following a disaster.<ref>{{Citation|title=Dharma Master Cheng Yen - Discovery Channel Documentary \u8b49\u56b4\u6cd5\u5e2b - Discovery \u983b\u9053 (\u4e2d\u6587\u5b57\u5e55) 480p|date=2014-03-01|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SHsDjv5JqbU|accessdate=2017-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525233639/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SHsDjv5JqbU|archive-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===People's Republic of China===\n\nTzu Chi's involvement with providing aid in the People's Republic of China was difficult at first. Cheng Yen has referred to relief work in [[China]] as \"Building a Bridge of Love.\" The initial problems with providing aid in China involved the [[Cross-Strait relations|political tensions]] between Taiwan and China and Communist China's disdain for religion. In Taiwan, it was difficult to convince [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]] to help the [[Chinese people|Chinese]], and in China, it was difficult to convince government officials normally wary of religious organizations to accept Tzu Chi.\n\nTzu Chi's involvement in the [[People's Republic of China]] began in 1991, when it undertook relief operations after [[Eastern China flood of 1991|severe floods hit central and eastern China]]. The aid provided to China was Tzu Chi's first major effort at international relief aid, it also allowed Tzu Chi to develop its principles of delivering aid and establish relations with the People's Republic of China. Since then, the foundation has built schools, nursing homes and entire villages, including infrastructure in poor inland areas, such as [[Guizhou]] province.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite journal|title=Outline of assistance given to Chinese provinces|url=http://taipei.tzuchi.org.tw/tzquart/book/book1/book1.htm|archivedate=2012-03-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305053915/http://taipei.tzuchi.org.tw/tzquart/book/book1/book1.htm|accessdate=2014-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOver the past twenty years, Tzu Chi expanded their humanitarian work and influence to 28 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions in China. Projects include relief work after major disasters like the [[2008 Sichuan earthquake|Sichuan earthquake]]; distribution of rice and goods to the poor; social programs like regular visits to the needy; [[scholarship]] programs to the less privileged students; medical missions like [[bone marrow donation]] and [[free clinics]]; and educational outings of environmental protection and recycling activities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=647%3Atzu-chi-opens-chinas-dirst-overseas-ngo-office&catid=77%3Amissionofcharity&Itemid=177&lang=en|title=Tzu Chi Opens China's 1st Overseas NGO Office|date=23 August 2010|publisher=Tzu Chi|access-date=30 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721184701/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=647:tzu-chi-opens-chinas-dirst-overseas-ngo-office&catid=77:missionofcharity&Itemid=177&lang=en|archive-date=21 July 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2008, Tzu Chi became the first organization represented by a non-Mainland resident to be registered with the Chinese government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/03/11/us-china-taiwan-religion-idUSPEK23024220080311|title=Atheist China gives nod to Taiwan Buddhist group|date=11 March 2008|work=Reuters|access-date=2 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924131857/http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/03/11/us-china-taiwan-religion-idUSPEK23024220080311|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the [[2008 Sichuan earthquake]], Tzu Chi sent food, blankets and medical aid to survivors, while volunteers in China set out for the disaster zone.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/national/national-news/2008/05/16/156647/p2/Jets-lift.htm|title=Jets lift life-saving aid materials to Sichuan|newspaper=[[The China Post]]|access-date=30 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925202225/http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/national/national-news/2008/05/16/156647/p2/Jets-lift.htm|archive-date=25 September 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tzu Chi was also one of the few organizations the Chinese government allowed to bring in aid workers from overseas to join the relief effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvbs.com.tw/NEWS/NEWS_LIST.asp?no=aj100920080513231527|title=Mainland authorities give approval to Tzu Chi \u2013 Tzu Chi team scheduled to depart tomorrow or the day after to join the relief effort|date=13 May 2008|publisher=[[TVBS]]|language=Chinese|accessdate=20 May 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517084044/http://www.tvbs.com.tw/NEWS/NEWS_LIST.asp?no=aj100920080513231527|archive-date=17 May 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/16/world/asia/16china.html|title=In Departure, China Invites Outside Help|date=16 May 2008|work=[[The New York Times]]|author1=French, Howard|author2=Wong, Edward|lastauthoramp=yes|access-date=23 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211124331/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/16/world/asia/16china.html|archive-date=11 December 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With the motto \"First to arrive, last to leave,\" the organization has continued with long-term reconstruction work in [[Sichuan]], and by 2010, had rebuilt thirteen schools in the region.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=793:new-schools-new-smiles&catid=77:missionofcharity&Itemid=177&lang=en|title=New Schools, New Smiles|last=Foundation|first=Tzu Chi|access-date=2017-04-29|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630215228/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=793%3Anew-schools-new-smiles&catid=77%3Amissionofcharity&Itemid=177&lang=en|archive-date=30 June 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, Tzu Chi became the first overseas NGO to receive permission from the Ministry of Civil Affairs to set up a nationwide charity foundation. Normally, overseas organizations must register with the Ministry of Commerce as businesses.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/faithworld/2010/08/20/taiwan-buddhist-charity-tzu-chi-sets-up-shop-in-atheist-china/|title=Taiwan Buddhist Charity Tzu Chi Sets Up Shop in Atheist China|date=20 August 2010|work=Reuters|access-date=30 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625164510/http://blogs.reuters.com/faithworld/2010/08/20/taiwan-buddhist-charity-tzu-chi-sets-up-shop-in-atheist-china/|archive-date=25 June 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The foundation received the China Charity Award from the Ministry of Civil Affairs for its work in charity and promoting the well-being of society in 2006 and again in 2008.\n\n=== Aid in Taiwan ===\nIn 1996, Tzu Chi started a nationwide volunteer program where volunteers are registered according to where they live with the goal of \"neighbors helping neighbors.\" The community volunteer initiative began as a disaster relief effort started in response to [[Typhoon Herb]].<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/local/archives/1999/10/03/0000004923|title=Tzuchi always ready to lend a helping hand - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2017-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=379:the-world-is-impermanent&catid=82:miscellaneous&Itemid=326&lang=en|title=The World is Impermanent|last=Foundation|first=Tzu Chi|access-date=2017-03-11|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015162351/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=379%3Athe-world-is-impermanent&catid=82%3Amiscellaneous&Itemid=326&lang=en|archive-date=15 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tzuchi.org.sg/eng/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=645&Itemid=566|title=Community Volunteers|website=www.tzuchi.org.sg|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810185022/http://www.tzuchi.org.sg/eng/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=645&Itemid=566|archive-date=2016-08-10|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-03-11}}</ref>\n[[File:Tzu Chi Food Booth Service for Rescue Team 20150204.jpg|thumb|Tzu Chi tent at rescue site]]\nTzu Chi volunteers were one of the first responders in the [[1999 Chi-Chi earthquake|Chi-Chi earthquake]] (known in Taiwan as the 921 earthquake) of 1999, mobilizing within 2 hours to provide thousands of sets of food and relief supplies to victims. The volunteers followed a strict system of organization where commissioners and teams of volunteers were assigned to specific townships, and teams were assigned to specific areas within the townships. This organizational structure was what allowed the volunteers to be mobilized so quickly and efficiently.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/local/archives/1999/10/03/0000004923/1|title=Tzuchi always ready to lend a helping hand - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2017-03-11}}</ref>  The earthquake prompted Cheng Yen to start \"Project Hope\", a long term project to rebuild 51 schools for those effected by the disaster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=123&Itemid=366&lang=en|title=Project Hope \u2014 Disaster Risk Reduction|website=tw.tzuchi.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610072518/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=123&Itemid=366&lang=en|archive-date=10 June 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1099&Itemid=248|title=Annual Statistics on the Schools Rebuilt by Tzu Chi|last=Foundation|first=Tzu Chi|access-date=2017-03-11|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627151000/http://www.tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1099&Itemid=248|archive-date=27 June 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tzu Chi raised more relief funds for the earthquake than any other religious organization in Taiwan, raising nearly sixty times as much funds for the relief effort than the next largest fund raiser, [[Fo Guang Shan]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jBmpT_H3ZFUC&pg=SA9-PA364&dq=tzu+chi+disaster+relief#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20disaster%20relief&f=false|title=Community Disaster Recovery and Resiliency: Exploring Global Opportunities and Challenges|last=Miller|first=DeMond S.|last2=Rivera|first2=Jason David|date=2016-04-19|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9781420088236|location=|pages=452|language=en}}</ref> The 921 earthquake was credited for prompting Tzu Chi to create a disaster relief coordination center at its headquarters to organize quicker disaster response services.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jBmpT_H3ZFUC&pg=SA9-PA364&dq=tzu+chi+disaster+relief#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20disaster%20relief&f=false|title=Community Disaster Recovery and Resiliency: Exploring Global Opportunities and Challenges|last=Miller|first=DeMond S.|last2=Rivera|first2=Jason David|date=2016-04-19|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9781420088236|location=|pages=454|language=en}}</ref>\n\nTzu Chi was also active in providing aid after [[Typhoon Nepartak (2016)|Typhoon Nepartak]] struck Taiwan in 2016, providing relief supplies, rebuilding communities, and providing medical care through its medical support staff in [[Taimali, Taitung|Taimali]], Taiwan which have been holding medical outreach free clinics in the area since 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/china-taiwan-province/tzu-chi-s-medical-care-survivors-after-typhoon-nepartak-taiwan|title=Tzu Chi's medical care for the survivors after Typhoon Nepartak in Taiwan|date=2016-08-24|work=ReliefWeb|access-date=2017-04-29|language=English|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825170213/http://reliefweb.int/report/china-taiwan-province/tzu-chi-s-medical-care-survivors-after-typhoon-nepartak-taiwan|archive-date=25 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1396:tzu-chi-begins-relief-work-in-southeast-taiwan-after-typhoon&catid=1:taiwan&Itemid=263&lang=en|title=Tzu Chi Begins Relief Work in Southeast Taiwan After Typhoon|work=Tzu Chi Foundation|access-date=2017-04-29|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206100816/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1396%3Atzu-chi-begins-relief-work-in-southeast-taiwan-after-typhoon&catid=1%3Ataiwan&Itemid=263&lang=en|archive-date=6 February 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== International Disaster Relief ===\nTzu Chi has participated in numerous other relief projects around the world, including sending teams to [[Indonesia]] and [[Sri Lanka]] in the wake of the [[tsunami]] resulting from the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake]] as well as to [[Pakistan]] after the [[2005 Kashmir earthquake|2005 earthquake]] in their northern mountains.  The later was done despite poor relations between the governments of the two countries.\n\nIn the aftermath of [[Hurricane Sandy]], the organization announced on 18 November 2012 a donation of $10 million in the form of $300 and $600 [[Visa Inc.|Visa]] debit cards to those affected in the [[New York (state)|New York]] and New Jersey area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qgazette.com/news/2012-11-28/Front_Page/Liu_Announces_Buddhist_Tzu_Chi_Donation_Of_10_Mill.html|title=Liu, Announces Buddhist Tzu Chi Donation Of $10 Million|date=28 November 2012|publisher=[[The Queens Gazette]]|accessdate=4 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209064352/http://www.qgazette.com/news/2012-11-28/Front_Page/Liu_Announces_Buddhist_Tzu_Chi_Donation_Of_10_Mill.html|archive-date=9 December 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Volunteers handed out these cards in parts of [[Brooklyn]], [[Queens]], and [[Staten Island]]. Tzu Chi was also active in providing aid following the [[April 2015 Nepal earthquake|2015 Nepal Earthquake]]. Tzu Chi was also active in relief efforts during [[Hurricane Harvey]] in 2017, the group provided aid, as well as cash gifts for those who helped the community during the disaster.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://abc13.com/buddhists-come-to-aid-of-officers-hit-by-harvey/2433855/|title=Buddhists come to aid of officers hit by Harvey|last=Carson|first=Ilona|date=2017-09-20|work=ABC13 Houston|access-date=2017-10-05|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005100945/http://abc13.com/buddhists-come-to-aid-of-officers-hit-by-harvey/2433855/|archive-date=5 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local/hurricane-relief-effort/Op6XVN0u36UWqUgShrE8YP/|title=Hurricane relief effort|last=Broady|first=Arlinda|website=ajc|access-date=2017-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005154535/http://www.ajc.com/news/local/hurricane-relief-effort/Op6XVN0u36UWqUgShrE8YP/|archive-date=5 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2017/09/15/appreciation-frustration-harvey-evacuees-dallas/|title=Appreciation Turns To Frustration For Some Harvey Evacuees In Dallas|access-date=2017-10-05|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005151229/http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2017/09/15/appreciation-frustration-harvey-evacuees-dallas/|archive-date=5 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2016, the organization distributed in the United States over $2 million in cash cards to disaster victims.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lionsroar.com/buddhist-organization-tzu-chi-distributing-humanitarian-relief-in-houston-after-hurricane-harvey/|title=Buddhist organization Tzu Chi distributing humanitarian relief in Houston after Hurricane Harvey|date=2017-09-01|work=Lion's Roar|access-date=2017-09-04|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904111803/https://www.lionsroar.com/buddhist-organization-tzu-chi-distributing-humanitarian-relief-in-houston-after-hurricane-harvey/|archive-date=4 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of 2015, Tzu Chi has provided disaster relief aid to over 85 countries worldwide.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5BaMBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=tzu+chi+disaster+relief#v=onepage&q=85%20countries&f=false|title=Taiwan's Marginalized Role in International Security: Paying a Price|last=Glaser|first=Bonnie S.|last2=Vitello|first2=Jacqueline A.|date=2015-01-21|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781442240605|location=|pages=28|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Global presence==\nTzu Chi's headquarters is in [[Hualien County]], Taiwan.\n<gallery>\nFile:Jing Si Abode.jpg|Jing Si Abode (\u9759\u601d\u7cbe\u820d) of Tzu Chi Foundation\nFile:Tzu Chi Foundation Facade, Hualien (3990381753).jpg|The Hall of Still Thoughts. The Tzu Chi General Hospital is on the right\nFile:Tzu Chi Foundation (Hong Kong).jpg|Tzu-Chi Foundation in Hong Kong\nFile:The usual set up for the Tzu Chi 3-in-1 Celebration (\u6d74\u4f5b\u5178\u79ae).jpg|The usual set up for the Tzu Chi 3-in-1 Celebration (\u6d74\u4f5b\u5178\u79ae)\nFile:Tzu Chi Culture and Communication Foundation 20160607b.jpg|Tzu Chi Culture and Communication building\n</gallery>\n\n===Portfolios===\n\nTzu Chi's portfolios include case management, medical, educational and [[disaster relief]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Tzu Chi Foundation Finds Good Karma in Disaster Relief and Preparedness|url=https://www.nyredcross.org/?nd=news_room_detail&news_id=53&jid=63915|publisher=[[American Red Cross]]|accessdate=14 October 2012|date=23 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121228094810/https://www.nyredcross.org/?nd=news_room_detail&news_id=53&jid=63915|archivedate=28 December 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe organization builds and operates many hospitals and schools, with outreach efforts that range from visits to nursing homes to providing bone marrow surgery, as well as offering items such as washing machines to struggling single mothers. The television \"Da Ai\" network operates with its own news and television programming. Chinese schools have also been established abroad, such as in Australia and the United States, which apart from teaching Chinese and [[sign language]] also guides students in ways of compassion and [[community service]].\n[[File:US Navy 100226-N-6214F-040 Members of the Bouddhiste Tzu Chi Foundation, a Buddist charity based in Taiwan, distribute about 2,000 blankets and tarps to Haitian citizens.jpg|thumb|Tzu Chi volunteers distribute blankets to victims of the [[2010 Haiti earthquake|2010 Haitian Earthquake]]]]\n\n===Recycling===\n\nA significant fraction of funds raised by Tzu Chi revolves around [[environmentally friendly]] goals in encouraging the recycling of items such as water bottles as well as using reusable items or reusing items to reduce waste.\n\nAs of 2014, the foundation operates over 5,600 recycling stations.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-taiwan-recycling-20141117-story.html|title=Taiwan Buddhists transform plastic waste|last=Jennings|first=Ralph|date=17 Nov 2014|website=latimes.com|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116175356/http://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-taiwan-recycling-20141117-story.html|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> One of the foundation's projects is the recycling of [[polyethylene terephthalate]] (PET) plastic bottles for the production of textiles. The project, which was started in 2006, collects PET plastic bottles and recycles them into cloth.<ref>Tzu Chi Quarterly, Winter 2008</ref> The project is handled by the Tzu Chi sponsored non-profit Da Ai Technology Co. The products are all designed by members of the paid staff and recycled plastic bottles make up about half of the raw materials for the products. The project collects about 2,000 tons of plastic bottles each year.<ref name=\":2\" /> Tzu Chi's recycling centers have been a source of criticism however, with critics arguing that Tzu Chi's recycling efforts result in lost income for poor trash collectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2014/04/23/2003588703|title=Tzu Chi said to steal from poor - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, the foundation has produced over 460,000 polyester blankets out of recycled plastic bottles, many of which have been distributed as part of Tzu Chi's disaster relief programs throughout the world. Other items made with the recycled resins include thermal underwear, T-shirts, hospital bed sheets, medical gowns, suitcases, stuffed animals and uniforms for Tzu Chi volunteers. While the project relies on recycled plastic bottles for the production of its products, its leaders have stated that it is still best for people to not use plastic bottles at all.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=300:a-greener-blanket&catid=59:internationalrelief&Itemid=183&lang=en|title=A Greener Blanket|last=Foundation|first=Tzu Chi|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927052415/http://www.tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=300:a-greener-blanket&catid=59:internationalrelief&Itemid=183&lang=en|archive-date=27 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://phys.org/news/2013-03-taiwan-plastic-junk-blankets-dolls.html|title=Taiwan turns plastic junk into blankets, dolls|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116183046/https://phys.org/news/2013-03-taiwan-plastic-junk-blankets-dolls.html|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n[[File:Tzu Chi Foundation in Hualien (3991128820).jpg|thumb|Inside the main hall of Tzu Chi Foundation]]\n\n===Dharma===\n\nThe teachings of the [[Buddha]] and founder Master Cheng Yen play a core role in the workings of the organization. \"Tzu Chi Day\" is celebrated every year on the second Sunday of May which generally coincides with the Buddha's birthday ([[Vesak Day]]), and [[Mother's Day]] (as recognised in Taiwan). Celebrations during Tzu Chi Day include the bathing of the Buddha ceremony, the tradition's message is that it is the people that need cleansing before they become better individuals. Tzu Chi promotes many of the teachings of Buddhism, in particular the [[Lotus Sutra]], \nand also has sutra adaptations through the use of sign language on the [[Innumerable Meanings Sutra|Sutra of the Innumerable Meanings]], which teaches that sentient existence is challenging and filled with disasters in the absence of observations of [[\u015a\u012bla|virtue]], as well as the [[Water Repentence|Sutra of the Water Repentance]], which advocates and symbolizes the need to repent [[karma|karmic transgressions]]. Despite these activities, Tzu Chi has a policy of not proselytizing religion directly at its public activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/visit-to-the-tzu-chi-foundation-in-taiwan/238309/|title=Visit to the Tzu Chi Foundation in Taiwan - The Manila Times Online|website=www.manilatimes.net|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906092112/http://www.manilatimes.net/visit-to-the-tzu-chi-foundation-in-taiwan/238309/|archive-date=6 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/114046/tzu-chi-foundation-lets-hear-it-for-amazing-buddhist-responders|title=Tzu Chi Foundation: Let's hear it for amazing Buddhist responders|last=Petilla|first=Danny|website=globalnation.inquirer.net|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116182921/https://globalnation.inquirer.net/114046/tzu-chi-foundation-lets-hear-it-for-amazing-buddhist-responders|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Apart from being non-proselytist, Tzu Chi's adaptation of Buddhist principles is [[apolitical]].\n\nIn disaster regions where a particular religious faith is prominent, Tzu Chi regularly works together with local religious organizations. Tzu Chi has re-built [[mosques]] and [[church (building)|churches]] in disaster zones where faith plays an important role in local society.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzdyNvcRTWk|title=Master Cheng Yen and Tzu Chi|publisher=The Discovery Channel|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110210357/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzdyNvcRTWk|archive-date=10 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTzu Chi nuns ([[bhikkhuni]]s) do not rely on donations for their livelihood, something uncommon among most Buddhist orders. In earlier days, the nuns sustained themselves by farming, weaving and other handicrafts. More recently, they sustained themselves by the manufacture of electrical circuit breakers and other products.\n\n===International branches===\n\nTzu Chi has branches in 47 countries and regions including USA, Canada, Australia, [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], Malaysia, [[Singapore]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Tzu Chi Singapore|url=https://zh-tw.facebook.com/tzuchisingapore|website=Facebook|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref> and various locations in Asia, Europe and Africa.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tzuchi.org/global/offices/index.html | title=Tzu Chi Local Chapters and Associations | publisher=Buddhist Compassion Relief Tzu Chi Foundation | accessdate=29 December 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404090834/http://www.tzuchi.org/GLOBAL/offices/index.html | archivedate=4 April 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n[[File:Da Ai building of Tzu Chi University.JPG|thumb|Building for Tzu Chi's Buddhist Satellite station, Da Ai Television]]\n\n===Television and Satellite Network===\n\nOn 17 August 1999, a television network was formed in Taiwan under the Tzu Chi Foundation of the Culture of Communication, Inc with the slogan \"Love to make the world light up\". Formally known as [[Da Ai Television]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Da Ai Television|url=http://www.daai.tv/daai-web/main/|publisher=Tzu Chi Culture and Communication Foundation|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020103914/http://www.daai.tv/daai-web/main/|archive-date=20 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the network grew into a global broadcasting presence with offerings of a radio service,<ref>{{cite web|title=radio.newdaai.tv|url=http://radio.newdaai.tv/aod/index_in.php|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910195337/http://radio.newdaai.tv/aod/index_in.php|archive-date=10 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tzu Chi Channel 1, Tzu Chi Channel 2, Da Ai TV Indonesia, Da Ai TV Thailand, and Da Ai TV Egypt. Live streaming of Channel 1 and 2 can also be found on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u5927\u611b\u96fb\u8996\u4e00\u81fa Live \u76f4\u64ad|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ukWk-Gy0NT8|website=Youtube|publisher=Tzu Chi DaAiVideo|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220132054/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ukWk-Gy0NT8|archive-date=20 December 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Jing Si Books & Caf\u00e9===\n\nJing Si Books & Caf\u00e9 is a chain of non-profit bookstores and cafes operated by Tzu Chi offering Tzu Chi merchandise and publications by [[Cheng Yen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jing Si Books & Cafe|url=http://jingsi.com.tw/|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911002133/http://jingsi.com.tw/|archive-date=11 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Youth==\n\nThe Tzu Chi Collegiate Association (\u6148\u6fdf\u5927\u5c08\u9752\u5e74\u806f\u8abc\u6703) is the Foundation's college youth organization,<ref>{{cite web|title=Tzu Chi Collegiate Association (Singapore)|url=http://sgtzuching2014en.wordpress.com|website=\u6148\u6fdf\u5927\u5c08\u9752\u5e74\u806f\u8abc\u6703\uff08\u65b0\u52a0\u5761\uff09|publisher=WordPress.com|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910195926/http://sgtzuching2014en.wordpress.com/|archive-date=10 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and was officially established in Taiwan on 31 May 1992. With chapters at universities worldwide, its goal is to allow university students (known as Tzu Ching or \u6148\u9752, literally \"compassionate youth\") to be involved with Tzu Chi's activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore Tzu Ching \u65b0\u52a0\u5761\u6148\u9752|url=http://sgtzuching3in1.blogspot.sg|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911001701/http://sgtzuching3in1.blogspot.sg/|archive-date=11 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What is Tzu Ching|url=http://www.umich.edu/~tzuching/|work=Tzu Chi Collegiate Association at the University of Michigan|publisher=[[University of Michigan]]|accessdate=22 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222213236/http://www.umich.edu/~tzuching/|archive-date=22 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tzu Ching volunteers are given the opportunity to participate in large-scale events such as disaster relief and international NGO conferences such as the annual [[UN Youth Assembly]]. Master Cheng Yen encourages the Tzu Ching volunteers to actively communicate with each other, with the goals of learning and improving. Each year an international Tzu Ching officer training retreat camp is held at the foundation headquarters in [[Hualien City|Hualien]].\n\nTzu Shao (\u6148\u5c11) is the Tzu Chi branch for youths under the age of 18. People in this group do community services such as free clinics, soup kitchens, and nursery homes.\n\n==Year End Ceremonies==\n\nEach year Tzu Chi conducts a Year End Ceremony attended by Tzu Chi workers, volunteers and members in January or February where Master [[Cheng Yen]] distributes blessings in the form of red packets that embosses a coin in Taiwanese currency{{Refn|The coin symbolizes the fifty cents the thirty housewives saved at the founding of Tzu Chi|group=note}} together with auspicious words for the coming year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tzu Chi Year End Ceremony 2013|url=http://yeb.tzuchi.org.sg|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910200034/http://yeb.tzuchi.org.sg/|archive-date=10 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=note|20em}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Yu-Shuang Yao|title=Taiwan's Tzu Chi as Engaged Buddhism: Origins, Organization, Appeal and Social Impact|url=|date=2012|publisher=Global Oriental|isbn=978-90-04-21747-8}}\n* Gombrich, Richard (2013). [https://www.uni-marburg.de/fb03/ivk/mjr/pdfs/2013/reviews/rev_gombrich_2013.pdf Review: Yu-Shuang Yao, Taiwan's Tzu Chi as Engaged Buddhism: Origins, Organization, Appeal and Social Impact, Global Oriental 2012]. Marburg Journal of Religion 17 (1), 1-8\n* {{cite book|author=C. Julia Huang|title=Charisma and Compassion: Cheng Yen and the Buddhist Tzu Chi Movement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t529SPeue5MC|year=2009|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-03133-3}}\n* Jones, Charles B. (2009). [http://www.globalbuddhism.org/jgb/index.php/jgb/article/view/99/113 Modernization and Traditionalism in Buddhist Almsgiving: The Case of the Buddhist Compassion Relief Tzu-chi Association in Taiwan]. Journal of Global Buddhism 10, 291-319\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/ Official Site (Global Homepage)]\n*[http://www.tzuchi.us/ Official Site (USA)]\n*[http://www.books.com.tw/exep/assp.php/jamezku/products/F012089631 TzuChi, Serving with Compassion (English Guideline)]\n\n{{Commons category|Tzu Chi}}\n{{Four Great Mountains}}\n\n[[Category:Tzu Chi| ]]\n[[Category:Buddhist organizations based in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:International charities]]\n[[Category:International volunteer organizations]]\n[[Category:Religious service organizations]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1966]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox monastery\n| image          =File:Tzu Chi Logo.jpg\n| caption        = Tzu Chi's [[Nelumbo nucifera|lotus]] Logo.\n| name           = Tzu Chi Foundation\n| full           = Buddhist Compassion Relief Tzu Chi Foundation, Taiwan\n| native_name    = \u6148\u6fdf\u57fa\u91d1\u6703\n| native_name_lang = zh\n| established    = 1966\n| order          = [[Mahayana]]\n| founder        = [[Cheng Yen]]\n| abbot          = [[Cheng Yen]]\n| location       = [[Hualien City|Hualien]], [[Taiwan]]\n| coord          = \n| public_access  = \n| other_info     = \n|website={{url|http://tw.tzuchi.org/en}}}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| t       = \u8ca1\u5718\u6cd5\u4eba\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u4f5b\u654e\u6148\u6fdf\u6148\u5584\u4e8b\u696d\u57fa\u91d1\u6703\n| s       = \u8d22\u56e2\u6cd5\u4eba\u4e2d\u534e\u6c11\u56fd\u4f5b\u654e\u6148\u6d4e\u6148\u5584\u4e8b\u4e1a\u57fa\u91d1\u4f1a\n| bpmf    = \u3118\u311e\u02ca\u310a\u3128\u3122\u02ca\u3108\u311a\u02c7\u3116\u3123\u02ca\u3113\u3128\u3125 \u310f\u3128\u311a\u02ca\u3107\u3127\u3123\u02ca\u310d\u3128\u311b\u02ca\u3108\u311b\u02ca\u3110\u3127\u3120\u02cb\u3118\u02ca\u3110\u3127\u02cb\u3118\u02ca\u3115\u3122\u02cb\u3115\u02cb\u3127\u311d\u02cb\u3110\u3127 \u3110\u3127\u3123 \u310f\u3128\u311f\u02cb\n| p       = C\u00e1itu\u00e1n F\u01cer\u00e9n Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 M\u00edngu\u00f3 F\u00f3ji\u00e0o C\u00ed J\u00ec C\u00edsh\u00e0n Sh\u00ecy\u00e8 J\u012bj\u012bn Hu\u00ec\n| altname = Short name\n| t2      = \u6148\u6fdf\u57fa\u91d1\u6703\n| s2      = \u6148\u6d4e\u57fa\u91d1\u4f1a\n| p2      = C\u00ed j\u00ec j\u012bj\u012bn hu\u00ec\n| poj2    = Ch\u00fb-ch\u00e8 ki-kim-h\u014de\n}}\n{{buddhism}}\n\n'''Buddhist Compassion Relief Tzu Chi Foundation, Republic of China''', known for short as the '''Tzu Chi Foundation''' ({{lang-zh|t=\u6148\u6fdf\u57fa\u91d1\u6703|p=C\u00ed J\u00ec j\u012bj\u012bn hu\u00ec|l=\"Compassionate Relief Foundation\"}}), is a [[Taiwan]]ese international humanitarian and non-governmental organization (NGO). The foundation has several sub-organizations such as the Tzu Chi International Medical Association (TIMA) and also the Tzu Chi Collegiate Youth Association (Tzu Ching) ({{zh|t=\u6148\u6fdf\u5927\u5c08\u9751\u5e74\u806f\u8abc\u6703 (\u6148\u9751))}}. Tzu Chi volunteers and relief workers are mostly recognizable by their blue and white uniforms called, in {{zh|t=\u85cd\u5929\u767d\u96f2}}, ''l\u00e1nti\u0101n b\u00e1iy\u00fan'', ( lit. 'blue sky, white clouds'). The foundation's work includes medical aid, disaster relief, and environmental work such as recycling. It is operated by a worldwide network of volunteers and employees and has been awarded a special consultative status at the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]].<ref>O'Neill, Mark (2010), ''[http://www.books.com.tw/exep/assp.php/jamezku/products/F012089631 Tzu Chi: Serving With Compassion]'', John Wiley & Sons</ref> \n\nThe Tzu Chi Foundation was founded by Master [[Cheng Yen]], a Taiwanese Buddhist nun, or ''[[bhikkhuni]]'', in 1966 as a Buddhist humanitarian organization. The organization began as a group of thirty housewives who saved money for needy families. Tzu Chi gradually expanded its services over time, opening a free medical clinic in 1972 and building its first hospital in 1986. The organization underwent a rapid expansion in the late 1980s and early 1990s, coinciding with a surge of popularity in [[Humanistic Buddhism]] in Taiwan. In the 1990s the organization started major international disaster relief efforts. Tzu Chi is known for undertaking long term projects such as building new homes, schools, hospitals, and places of worship (including churches and mosques for non-Buddhists) for victims following a disaster. As of 2013, the organization was estimated at over 10 million members worldwide throughout 47 countries. \n\nTzu Chi has a policy of being secular in its humanitarian work, however [[Dharma (Buddhism)|Dharma]] teachings are often integrated into its practices for volunteers. Cheng Yen is considered to be one of the \"[[Four Heavenly Kings (Taiwan)|Four Heavenly Kings]]\" of Taiwanese Buddhism, and Tzu Chi itself is considered to be one of the \"[[Four Great Mountains (Taiwan)|Four Great Mountains]]\", or four major Buddhist organizations of Taiwan along with [[Fo Guang Shan]], [[Dharma Drum Mountain]], and [[Chung Tai Shan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://info.taiwan.net.tw/tourbusE/december_page1.html |title=Come to Taiwan, Return with good memories |publisher=Info.taiwan.net.tw |accessdate=2012-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227183910/http://info.taiwan.net.tw/tourbusE/december_page1.html |archivedate=27 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shuai|first=J. J.|last2=Chen|first2=H. C.|last3=Chang|first3=C. H.|date=2010-12-01|title=Visualization of the Taiwaness Buddhism web based on social network analysis|journal=2010 International Computer Symposium (ICS2010)|pages=187\u2013191|doi=10.1109/COMPSYM.2010.5685523|df=dmy-all|isbn=978-1-4244-7639-8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wvGWJcQ3ZX0C&dq=four+heavenly+kings+taiwan+tzu+chi&q=four+heavenly+kings+|title=2600 Years of Sambuddhatva: Global Journey of Awakening|date=2011-01-01|isbn=9789559349334|pages=282|language=en|access-date=4 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410133539/https://books.google.com/books?id=wvGWJcQ3ZX0C&dq=four+heavenly+kings+taiwan+tzu+chi&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=four+heavenly+kings+|archive-date=10 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n==History==\n\nThe Tzu Chi Foundation was founded as a charity organization with [[Buddhist]] origins by the Buddhist nun Master [[Cheng Yen]] in 1966 in [[Hualien City|Hualien]], Taiwan after Cheng Yen saw the humanitarian work of Christian missionaries in Taiwan in the [[Taiwan after World War II|post World War II period]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion|last=O'Neill|first=Mark|date=2010-05-17|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=19|language=en}}</ref> She was inspired by her master and mentor, the late Venerable Master [[Yin Shun]] (\u5370\u9806\u5c0e\u5e2b, Y\u00ecn Sh\u00f9n d\u01ceosh\u012b) a proponent of [[Humanistic Buddhism]], who exhorted her to \"work for Buddhism and for all sentient beings\". The organization began with a motto of \"instructing the rich and saving the poor\" as a group of thirty [[housewives]] who saved fifty [[New Taiwan dollar|cents]] ([[US$]]0.02) every day and stored them in bamboo savings banks to donate to needy families.<ref name=\"parabola\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parabola.org/the-desire-to-relieve-all-suffering|title=THE DESIRE TO RELIEVE ALL SUFFERING|date=2010|publisher=Parabola Magazine|last1=Wolkstein|first1=Diane|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923002225/http://www.parabola.org/the-desire-to-relieve-all-suffering|archivedate=23 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of Dharma Master Cheng Yen|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=159%3Aintroduction&catid=81%3Aabout&Itemid=198&lang=en|website=tw.tzuchi.org|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823142309/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=159%3Aintroduction&catid=81%3Aabout&Itemid=198&lang=en|archive-date=23 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTzu Chi experienced modest growth in the first two decades of its establishment, it grew to 293 members in 1968 and by 1986 had just 8,000 members.<ref name=\"chinaperspectives.revues.org\" /> The foundation gradually expanded its services since starting as a group of thirty housewives, raising money for disaster relief after a small fire in 1970 that destroyed 43 buildings and opening its first free medical clinic in 1972.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion|last=O'Neill|first=Mark|date=2010-05-17|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=22|language=en}}</ref> In 1986 the foundation established its first hospital in [[Hualien City]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nWith the surge in popularity of [[Humanistic Buddhism]] in Taiwan in the late 1980s and 1990s, and the publicity from fundraising to build its first hospital, Tzu Chi enjoyed a rapid expansion in membership alongside several other major Taiwanese Buddhist organizations during this time.<ref name=\":25\"/><ref name=\"chinaperspectives.revues.org\" /> From 1987 to 1991, Tzu Chi membership doubled in size each year, by 1994, it boasted a membership of 4 million members.<ref name=\"chinaperspectives.revues.org\">{{cite journal|last1=Schak|first1=David|last2=Hsiao|first2=Hsin-Huang Michael|title=Taiwan's Socially Engaged Buddhist Groups|journal=China Perspectives|volume=2005|date=2005|issue=59|df=dmy-all|doi=10.4000/chinaperspectives.2803}}</ref> Tzu Chi's expanded its aid work to the [[People's Republic of China]] in 1991, during the [[Eastern China flood of 1991|eastern China floods]].<ref name=\":5\" /> In 1993, the foundation created a bone marrow registry, an effort that eventually caused Taiwan to alter its bone marrow laws, and organized a nationwide volunteer program for Taiwan in 1996.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nThe foundation achieved much media attention in Taiwan in 2015 with a plan to develop a plot of land in [[Neihu District]] into a disaster relief center and cultural park which led to the destruction of parts of the Neihu conservation zone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/asoc/201503160028.aspx|title=City officials, Neihu residents welcome Tzu Chi's project pullback {{!}} Society {{!}} FOCUS TAIWAN - CNA ENGLISH NEWS|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref><ref name=\"taipeitimes.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2015/03/17/2003613729|title=Tzu Chi retracts controversial project - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2015/03/11/2003613258/1|title=Tzu Chi's Neihu land should be rejuvenated - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/local/taipei/2015/03/17/431281/City-officials.htm|title=City officials, Neihu residents welcome Tzu Chi retreat from project - The China Post|date=2015-04-14|access-date=2018-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414225114/http://chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/local/taipei/2015/03/17/431281/City-officials.htm|archive-date=14 April 2015}}</ref> The incident led to widespread critical coverage of Tzu Chi by the Taiwanese media, and scrutiny into its finances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2013/01/24/2003553308|title=Tzu Chi buildings spark protests - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref><ref name=\"taipeitimes.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chinapost.com.tw/editorial/taiwan-issues/2015/03/22/431650/Tzu-Chi.htm|title=Tzu Chi needs more transparency in charity work - The China Post|date=2015-03-24|access-date=2018-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324231306/http://chinapost.com.tw/editorial/taiwan-issues/2015/03/22/431650/Tzu-Chi.htm|archive-date=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?cid=1103&MainCatID=&id=20150319000091|title=Tzu Chi in Tainan school land rental subsidy controversy\uff5cWantChinaTimes.com|date=2015-04-14|access-date=2018-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414173534/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?cid=1103&MainCatID=&id=20150319000091|archive-date=14 April 2015}}</ref> During this time several [[Fake news|unsubstantiated reports]] circulated in Taiwan about the foundation, including unfounded claims that the foundation invested in tobacco and weapons companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20150322000132&cid=1701|title=Tzu Chi has admitted errors; it's time for compassion\uff5cWantChinaTimes.com|date=2015-04-14|access-date=2018-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414173530/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20150322000132&cid=1701|archive-date=14 April 2015}}</ref> Despite authorities not finding any illicit activity with its finances, calls for greater transparency were made.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20150303000052&cid=1103|title=Tzu Chi Foundation urged to publish detailed donation list|last=|first=|date=|work=Want China Times|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414173317/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20150303000052&cid=1103|archive-date=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nTzu Chi has grown to become a significant actor in civil society, Tzu Chi is not only the largest Buddhist organization in Taiwan,<ref name=\"chinaperspectives.revues.org2\">{{cite journal|last1=Schak|first1=David|last2=Hsiao|first2=Hsin-Huang Michael|date=2005|title=Taiwan's Socially Engaged Buddhist Groups|journal=China Perspectives|volume=2005|issue=59|df=dmy-all|doi=10.4000/chinaperspectives.2803}}</ref> but also Taiwan's largest owner of private land.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.taiwannews.com.tw/etn/news_content.php?id=2698712|title=Why Tzu Chi is sparking resentment|date=6 March 2016|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915192203/http://www.taiwannews.com.tw/etn/news_content.php?id=2698712|archive-date=15 September 2016|url-status=live|agency=Central News Agency|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of 2013, the organization was estimated to have approximately 10 million members worldwide, and chapters in 47 countries.<ref name=\":34\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzdyNvcRTWk|title=Master Cheng Yen and Tzu Chi|publisher=The Discovery Channel|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=293&Itemid=283&lang=en|title=Tzu Chi Missions|website=tw.tzuchi.org|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109072414/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=293&Itemid=283&lang=en|archive-date=9 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\n[[File:KL Tzu-Chi Jing Si Hall.jpg|thumb|Main hall at Tzu Chi Foundation]]\nThe four major causes of Tzu Chi are ''Charity'', ''Medicine'', ''Education'', and ''Humanity'', as highlighted by the official motto, or concept of \"Four endeavors, eight footprints\" ({{zh|t=\u56db\u5927\u5fd7\u696d\uff0c\u516b\u5927\u8173\u5370}}). The eight footprints are [[charity (practice)|charity]] causes, medical contributions, [[education]] development, humanities, international disaster assistance, bone-marrow donation, community volunteerism, and environmental protection.\n\nThe official website for the organization states that the organization started with Charity, and then extended its aims to include Medicine, Education and Culture. Its stated goal is to promote \"sincerity, integrity, trust, and honesty\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=293&Itemid=283&lang=en|title=Tzu Chi Missions|website=tw.tzuchi.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109072414/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=293&Itemid=283&lang=en|archive-date=9 November 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=15 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTzu Chi is notably distinct from the other [[Four Great Mountains (Taiwan)|Four Great Mountains]] in respect to three main unique characteristics. First of all, the founder of the organization is a female. Secondly, the founder is not a Buddhist scholar who promotes a specific interpretation of Buddhism nor started any kind of religious movement. And finally, the organization is officially a charitable organization and Tzu Chi itself focuses primarily on humanitarianism and community service rather than Buddhist spiritual development.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hsin-Huang Michael|first1=Hsiao|last2=Schak|first2=David|date=2005|title=Taiwan's Socially Engaged Buddhist Groups|url=https://chinaperspectives.revues.org/2803#tocto2n6|url-status=live|journal=China Perspectives|issue=59|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815194230/http://chinaperspectives.revues.org/2803#tocto2n6|archive-date=15 August 2016|accessdate=12 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Logo===\n\nConsisting of a ship that also simultaneously bears the lotus fruit and flower, the Tzu Chi logo symbolizes that the world can be made a better place by planting good karmic seeds. Followers believe that these seeds are required for flowers bloom and bear fruit, which is a metaphor for their beliefs that a better society can be created with good actions and pure thoughts. The ship represents Tzu Chi steering a ship of compassion, representing their goal in saving all beings that suffer, while the Eight Petals represent the [[Noble Eightfold Path]] in [[Buddhism]], which Tzu Chi uses as their guide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tzuchi.us/blog/tzu-chi-logo/|title=Tzu Chi Logo - Tzu Chi USA|website=www.tzuchi.us|access-date=2017-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709005113/https://www.tzuchi.us/blog/tzu-chi-logo/|archive-date=9 July 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Noble Eightfold Path consists of:\n# [[View (Buddhism)|Right View]]\n# [[Noble Eightfold Path#Right resolve|Right Thought]]\n# [[Noble Eightfold Path#Right speech|Right Speech]]\n# [[Noble Eightfold Path#Right action|Right Action]]\n# [[Noble Eightfold Path#Right livelihood|Right Livelihood]]\n# [[Noble Eightfold Path#Right effort|Right Effort]]\n# [[Sati (Buddhism)|Right Mindfulness]]\n# [[Right concentration|Right Focus]]\n\n===Tzu Chi's Ten Precepts===\n[[File:The Great Awakened of the Universe (\u5b87\u5b99\u5927\u89ba\u8457) is the depiction of Buddha of Tzu Chi Foundation. In the statue, Buddha is letting the world witness his enlightenment.jpg|thumb|Tzu Chi Foundation's depiction of the Buddha on a wall mural. The image is known as \"The Great Awakened of the Universe (\u5b87\u5b99\u5927\u89ba\u8457)\".]]Tzu Chi also has its own customized version of the [[Five Precepts|Buddhist Precepts]] as formulated by Master Cheng-Yen. The Ten Precepts of Tzu Chi are:\n\n#No killing\n# No stealing\n# No fornication\n# No lying\n# No drinking\n# No smoking or use of narcotics or [[betel nuts]]\n# No gambling\n# Practice [[filial piety]] and develop pleasant manners and speech\n# Abide by traffic laws\n# No participation in political activities or demonstrations\n\nMaster Cheng-Yen has stated that she developed these rules based on the new needs of modern society.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Ten Precepts of Tzu Chi|url=http://www.tzuchi.net/TCSC.nsf/0adbb3db1b96266f48256ae00021f8ae/9991505677819b0b48256ae8006b85c2|website=tzuchi.net|accessdate=3 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911071105/http://www.tzuchi.net/TCSC.nsf/0adbb3db1b96266f48256ae00021f8ae/9991505677819b0b48256ae8006b85c2|archive-date=11 September 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Medical Mission ==\nOne of the first major initiatives Tzu Chi took part in was the \"Tzu Chi Medical Mission\". This effort was inspired in 1970 after Cheng Yen noticed a link between poverty and illness after spending six years among the poor of eastern Taiwan.\n\nTzu Chi's first medical outreach occurred in 1972 when a free clinic was opened in [[Hualien City|Hualien]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://olbios.org/life-of-the-mother-teresa-of-asia/|title=Life of the \"Mother Teresa of Asia\" {{!}} Olbios|date=2016-01-26|work=Olbios|access-date=2017-03-18|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319115145/http://olbios.org/life-of-the-mother-teresa-of-asia/|archive-date=19 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Tzu Chi Hospital ===\n[[File:Hualien Tzu Chi General Hospital.JPG|thumb|Tzu Chi General Hospital in Hualien in 2011]]\nThe Foundation established its first Tzu Chi Hospital in [[Hualien City|Hualien]] in 1986. A 600-bed general hospital had been planned in 1979 to service the impoverished eastern coast of Taiwan.  A primary concern for Cheng Yen was that the area was isolated and the people in the area were cut off from aid during disasters.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC&dq=Tzu+Chi:+Serving+with+Compassion.|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion.|last=Mark.|first=O'Neill|date=2010-01-01|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=26|oclc=940634655}}</ref> Despite setbacks both in funding for the hospital and finding an acceptable site. Ground was broken on the site eventually chosen on 5 February 1983 at a ceremony officiated by then Provincial Governor (later President) [[Lee Teng-Hui]]. However, two weeks after ground was broken, Cheng Yen received a notice from the military telling her that the property was needed by the military and that construction would have to stop.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.tzuchi.com.tw/en/index.php/history/7-hualien-tzu-chi-hospital|title=Hualien Tzu Chi Hospital|access-date=2017-03-19|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052400/http://www.tzuchi.com.tw/en/index.php/history/7-hualien-tzu-chi-hospital|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XtDRTLTwD88C&dq=The+Life+and+Teachings+of+Venerable+Master+Cheng+Yen|title=Challenges The Life and Teachings of Venerable Master Cheng Yen|last=Gary|first=Ho|date=2014-01-01|publisher=Harbour Publishing|isbn=9781553659921|location=|pages=44|oclc=957463283}}</ref>\n\nA new site was obtained for the hospital with help from Minister of the Interior Lin Yang-kang.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC&dq=Tzu+Chi:+Serving+with+Compassion.|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion.|last=Mark.|first=O'Neill|date=2010-01-01|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=28|oclc=940634655}}</ref>  A second groundbreaking occurred on 2 April 1984 at the new site.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eng.tzuchi.my/index.php/culture/culture-news-k2/item/7498-50-years-of-tzu-chi-looking-back-and-striding-forward|title=50 Years of Tzu Chi: Looking Back and Striding Forward|access-date=2017-03-19|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052417/http://eng.tzuchi.my/index.php/culture/culture-news-k2/item/7498-50-years-of-tzu-chi-looking-back-and-striding-forward|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The publicity of the project to build the hospital led to a significant increase in the number of Tzu Chi volunteers, with Tzu Chi membership increasing six-fold by the time of the second groundbreaking since the announcement of the project in 1979.<ref name=\":25\"/> Construction was completed and the hospital opened on 17 August 1986.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nTzu Chi has since built hospitals in [[Yuli, Hualien|Yuli]], Hualien County; [[Dalin, Chiayi|Dalin]], [[Jiayi County]]; [[Guanshan, Taitung|Guanshan]], [[Taidong County]];  [[Tanzi District]], [[Taichung City]]; and [[Xindian District|Xindian]], [[New Taipei City]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=W4PuparQrsUC&pg=PA94&dq=tzu+chi+hospitals+yuli#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20hospitals%20yuli&f=false|title=The Politics of Buddhist Organizations in Taiwan, 1989-2003: Safeguard the Faith, Build a Pure Land, Help the Poor|last=Lalibert\u00e9|first=Andr\u00e9|date=2013-08-21|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134353545|location=|pages=94|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://app.tzuchi.com.tw/tzuchi_en/About_TP_Center/Default.htm|title=About Medicine Mission|last=|first=|date=|website=Buddhist Tzu Chi General Hospital|access-date=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to building hospitals the [[Tzu Chi College of Nursing]] was founded on 17 September 1989 in Hualien in order to address the shortage of nurses on Taiwan's east coast, with a focus on serving the poor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tzuchimedicalfoundation.org/about-tzu-chi/tzu-chi-missions/|title=Tzu Chi Missions|date=2014-12-03|work=BUDDHIST TZU CHI MEDICAL FOUNDATION|access-date=2017-04-29|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170429025148/http://www.tzuchimedicalfoundation.org/about-tzu-chi/tzu-chi-missions/|archive-date=29 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4dlOAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA127&dq=tzu+chi+nursing+college#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20nursing%20college&f=false|title=Ecofeminism and Globalization: Exploring Culture, Context, and Religion|last=Eaton|last2=Lorentzen|date=2004-09-08|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=9780585482767|location=|pages=127|language=en}}</ref> It was the first private nursing college in Taiwan to waive tuition for selected courses, in addition to providing full scholarships for qualified [[Taiwan aborigine]] students.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n=== Bone Marrow registry ===\n[[File:The Buddist Tzu Chi University.JPG|thumb|Main building at [[Tzu Chi University]]]]\nTzu Chi created a [[bone marrow]] registry, the Tzu Chi Bone Marrow Bank, in 1993 after a young follower of Cheng Yen was diagnosed with Leukemia.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XtDRTLTwD88C&pg=PA164&dq=tzu+chi+bone+marrow#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20bone%20marrow&f=false|title=Challenges: The Life and Teachings of Venerable Master Cheng Yen|last=Gary|date=2012-03-23|publisher=D & M Publishers|isbn=9781553659921|location=|pages=163|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":33\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC&pg=PA145&dq=tzu+chi+bone+marrow#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20bone%20marrow&f=false|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion|last=O'Neill|first=Mark|date=2010-05-17|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=145|language=en}}</ref>  Cheng Yen referred to the concept of bone marrow donation as a way to \"save a life without harming yourself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tzuchi.ca/index.php/en/about-us/tzu-chi-foundation|title=Tzu Chi Foundation|last=\u6148\u6fdf\u57fa\u91d1\u6703|access-date=2017-04-02|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402170105/http://www.tzuchi.ca/index.php/en/about-us/tzu-chi-foundation|archive-date=2 April 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This effort to register bone marrow donors from an organization with such massive membership like Tzu Chi caused Taiwan to change its laws regarding organ donations.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC&pg=PA145&dq=tzu+chi+bone+marrow#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20bone%20marrow&f=false|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion|last=O'Neill|first=Mark|date=2010-05-17|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=146|language=en}}</ref>{{refn|Prior to 1993 Taiwanese law only allowed organ transplants between relatives.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t--23FOImmIC&pg=PA145&dq=tzu+chi+bone+marrow#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20bone%20marrow&f=false|title=Tzu Chi: Serving with Compassion|last=O'Neill|first=Mark|date=2010-05-17|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470825679|location=|pages=146|language=en}}</ref>|group=note}} This registry became a division of the new Tzu Chi Stem Cells Center, which was founded to improve research and treatment capabilities.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=26vBBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA17&dq=Tzu+Chi+Stem+Cells+Center#v=onepage&q=Tzu%20Chi%20Stem%20Cells%20Center&f=false|title=Hematopoietic Cell Transplantation in Children with Cancer|last=Smith|first=Franklin O.|last2=Reaman|first2=Gregory H.|last3=Racadio|first3=Judy M.|date=2013-11-26|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9783642399206|location=|pages=17|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":33\"/> By 2007 the program had saved the lives of almost 1,500 people in 25 different countries.<ref name=\":33\" /> By 2008, Tzu Chi had registered more than 307,657 bone marrow donors.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XtDRTLTwD88C&pg=PA164&dq=tzu+chi+bone+marrow#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20bone%20marrow&f=false|title=Challenges: The Life and Teachings of Venerable Master Cheng Yen|last=Gary|date=2012-03-23|publisher=D & M Publishers|isbn=9781553659921|location=|pages=165|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== College of Medicine ===\nTzu Chi established the [[Tzu Chi College of Medicine]] in 1994.  This college became [[Tzu Chi University]] in 2000. In the meantime Cheng-Yen appealed to the Taiwanese public to donate their bodies for medical training, attempting to dispel traditional taboos in the process. As a result of this appeal, public support for [[body donation]]s surged nationwide. Consequently, at the Tzu Chi College of Medicine, there is one body for every four students to study as opposed to one body for every two hundred students at one school, the ratio is the lowest in the country.\n\nIn 1995, the Athletic Drug Testing Center was established at the request of the Ministry of Education and went into operation in 1996 during a national sporting event when gold medal winners were tested for banned drugs.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n== Disaster relief ==\n[[File:Tzu Chi Culture and Communication Foundation 20080309.jpg|thumb|Tzu Chi Culture and Communications building]]\nTzu Chi is most well known for its disaster relief efforts worldwide. In carrying out these projects, Tzu Chi has a policy that forbids public gatherings for the sole purpose of specific political, economic, and religious groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.us.tzuchi.org/usa/images/other/TzuChiFAQ-global.pdf|title=Frequently Asked Questions about Tzu Chi|last=|first=|date=2011-07-25|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725233133/http://www.us.tzuchi.org/usa/images/other/TzuChiFAQ-global.pdf|archive-date=25 July 2011|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> Tzu Chi volunteers are not to discuss business, politics, or preach religion while giving aid.<ref name=\":25\"/> One of the most iconic attributes of Tzu Chi disaster relief efforts is that volunteers not only provide short term aid but also partake in long term projects to rebuild the communities affected. Tzu Chi often builds new homes, schools, hospitals, and places of worship (including churches and mosques for non-Buddhists) for victims following a disaster.<ref>{{Citation|title=Dharma Master Cheng Yen - Discovery Channel Documentary \u8b49\u56b4\u6cd5\u5e2b - Discovery \u983b\u9053 (\u4e2d\u6587\u5b57\u5e55) 480p|date=2014-03-01|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SHsDjv5JqbU|accessdate=2017-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525233639/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SHsDjv5JqbU|archive-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===People's Republic of China===\n\nTzu Chi's involvement with providing aid in the People's Republic of China was difficult at first. Cheng Yen has referred to relief work in [[China]] as \"Building a Bridge of Love.\" The initial problems with providing aid in China involved the [[Cross-Strait relations|political tensions]] between Taiwan and China and Communist China's disdain for religion. In Taiwan, it was difficult to convince [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]] to help the [[Chinese people|Chinese]], and in China, it was difficult to convince government officials normally wary of religious organizations to accept Tzu Chi.\n\nTzu Chi's involvement in the [[People's Republic of China]] began in 1991, when it undertook relief operations after [[Eastern China flood of 1991|severe floods hit central and eastern China]]. The aid provided to China was Tzu Chi's first major effort at international relief aid, it also allowed Tzu Chi to develop its principles of delivering aid and establish relations with the People's Republic of China. Since then, the foundation has built schools, nursing homes and entire villages, including infrastructure in poor inland areas, such as [[Guizhou]] province.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite journal|title=Outline of assistance given to Chinese provinces|url=http://taipei.tzuchi.org.tw/tzquart/book/book1/book1.htm|archivedate=2012-03-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305053915/http://taipei.tzuchi.org.tw/tzquart/book/book1/book1.htm|accessdate=2014-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOver the past twenty years, Tzu Chi expanded their humanitarian work and influence to 28 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions in China. Projects include relief work after major disasters like the [[2008 Sichuan earthquake|Sichuan earthquake]]; distribution of rice and goods to the poor; social programs like regular visits to the needy; [[scholarship]] programs to the less privileged students; medical missions like [[bone marrow donation]] and [[free clinics]]; and educational outings of environmental protection and recycling activities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=647%3Atzu-chi-opens-chinas-dirst-overseas-ngo-office&catid=77%3Amissionofcharity&Itemid=177&lang=en|title=Tzu Chi Opens China's 1st Overseas NGO Office|date=23 August 2010|publisher=Tzu Chi|access-date=30 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721184701/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=647:tzu-chi-opens-chinas-dirst-overseas-ngo-office&catid=77:missionofcharity&Itemid=177&lang=en|archive-date=21 July 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2008, Tzu Chi became the first organization represented by a non-Mainland resident to be registered with the Chinese government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/03/11/us-china-taiwan-religion-idUSPEK23024220080311|title=Atheist China gives nod to Taiwan Buddhist group|date=11 March 2008|work=Reuters|access-date=2 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924131857/http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/03/11/us-china-taiwan-religion-idUSPEK23024220080311|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the [[2008 Sichuan earthquake]], Tzu Chi sent food, blankets and medical aid to survivors, while volunteers in China set out for the disaster zone.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/national/national-news/2008/05/16/156647/p2/Jets-lift.htm|title=Jets lift life-saving aid materials to Sichuan|newspaper=[[The China Post]]|access-date=30 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925202225/http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/national/national-news/2008/05/16/156647/p2/Jets-lift.htm|archive-date=25 September 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tzu Chi was also one of the few organizations the Chinese government allowed to bring in aid workers from overseas to join the relief effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvbs.com.tw/NEWS/NEWS_LIST.asp?no=aj100920080513231527|title=Mainland authorities give approval to Tzu Chi \u2013 Tzu Chi team scheduled to depart tomorrow or the day after to join the relief effort|date=13 May 2008|publisher=[[TVBS]]|language=Chinese|accessdate=20 May 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517084044/http://www.tvbs.com.tw/NEWS/NEWS_LIST.asp?no=aj100920080513231527|archive-date=17 May 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/16/world/asia/16china.html|title=In Departure, China Invites Outside Help|date=16 May 2008|work=[[The New York Times]]|author1=French, Howard|author2=Wong, Edward|lastauthoramp=yes|access-date=23 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211124331/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/16/world/asia/16china.html|archive-date=11 December 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With the motto \"First to arrive, last to leave,\" the organization has continued with long-term reconstruction work in [[Sichuan]], and by 2010, had rebuilt thirteen schools in the region.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=793:new-schools-new-smiles&catid=77:missionofcharity&Itemid=177&lang=en|title=New Schools, New Smiles|last=Foundation|first=Tzu Chi|access-date=2017-04-29|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630215228/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=793%3Anew-schools-new-smiles&catid=77%3Amissionofcharity&Itemid=177&lang=en|archive-date=30 June 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, Tzu Chi became the first overseas NGO to receive permission from the Ministry of Civil Affairs to set up a nationwide charity foundation. Normally, overseas organizations must register with the Ministry of Commerce as businesses.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/faithworld/2010/08/20/taiwan-buddhist-charity-tzu-chi-sets-up-shop-in-atheist-china/|title=Taiwan Buddhist Charity Tzu Chi Sets Up Shop in Atheist China|date=20 August 2010|work=Reuters|access-date=30 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625164510/http://blogs.reuters.com/faithworld/2010/08/20/taiwan-buddhist-charity-tzu-chi-sets-up-shop-in-atheist-china/|archive-date=25 June 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The foundation received the China Charity Award from the Ministry of Civil Affairs for its work in charity and promoting the well-being of society in 2006 and again in 2008.\n\n=== Aid in Taiwan ===\nIn 1996, Tzu Chi started a nationwide volunteer program where volunteers are registered according to where they live with the goal of \"neighbors helping neighbors.\" The community volunteer initiative began as a disaster relief effort started in response to [[Typhoon Herb]].<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/local/archives/1999/10/03/0000004923|title=Tzuchi always ready to lend a helping hand - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2017-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=379:the-world-is-impermanent&catid=82:miscellaneous&Itemid=326&lang=en|title=The World is Impermanent|last=Foundation|first=Tzu Chi|access-date=2017-03-11|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015162351/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=379%3Athe-world-is-impermanent&catid=82%3Amiscellaneous&Itemid=326&lang=en|archive-date=15 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tzuchi.org.sg/eng/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=645&Itemid=566|title=Community Volunteers|website=www.tzuchi.org.sg|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810185022/http://www.tzuchi.org.sg/eng/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=645&Itemid=566|archive-date=2016-08-10|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-03-11}}</ref>\n[[File:Tzu Chi Food Booth Service for Rescue Team 20150204.jpg|thumb|Tzu Chi tent at rescue site]]\nTzu Chi volunteers were one of the first responders in the [[1999 Chi-Chi earthquake|Chi-Chi earthquake]] (known in Taiwan as the 921 earthquake) of 1999, mobilizing within 2 hours to provide thousands of sets of food and relief supplies to victims. The volunteers followed a strict system of organization where commissioners and teams of volunteers were assigned to specific townships, and teams were assigned to specific areas within the townships. This organizational structure was what allowed the volunteers to be mobilized so quickly and efficiently.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/local/archives/1999/10/03/0000004923/1|title=Tzuchi always ready to lend a helping hand - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2017-03-11}}</ref>  The earthquake prompted Cheng Yen to start \"Project Hope\", a long term project to rebuild 51 schools for those effected by the disaster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=123&Itemid=366&lang=en|title=Project Hope \u2014 Disaster Risk Reduction|website=tw.tzuchi.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610072518/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=123&Itemid=366&lang=en|archive-date=10 June 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1099&Itemid=248|title=Annual Statistics on the Schools Rebuilt by Tzu Chi|last=Foundation|first=Tzu Chi|access-date=2017-03-11|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627151000/http://www.tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1099&Itemid=248|archive-date=27 June 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tzu Chi raised more relief funds for the earthquake than any other religious organization in Taiwan, raising nearly sixty times as much funds for the relief effort than the next largest fund raiser, [[Fo Guang Shan]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jBmpT_H3ZFUC&pg=SA9-PA364&dq=tzu+chi+disaster+relief#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20disaster%20relief&f=false|title=Community Disaster Recovery and Resiliency: Exploring Global Opportunities and Challenges|last=Miller|first=DeMond S.|last2=Rivera|first2=Jason David|date=2016-04-19|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9781420088236|location=|pages=452|language=en}}</ref> The 921 earthquake was credited for prompting Tzu Chi to create a disaster relief coordination center at its headquarters to organize quicker disaster response services.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jBmpT_H3ZFUC&pg=SA9-PA364&dq=tzu+chi+disaster+relief#v=onepage&q=tzu%20chi%20disaster%20relief&f=false|title=Community Disaster Recovery and Resiliency: Exploring Global Opportunities and Challenges|last=Miller|first=DeMond S.|last2=Rivera|first2=Jason David|date=2016-04-19|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9781420088236|location=|pages=454|language=en}}</ref>\n\nTzu Chi was also active in providing aid after [[Typhoon Nepartak (2016)|Typhoon Nepartak]] struck Taiwan in 2016, providing relief supplies, rebuilding communities, and providing medical care through its medical support staff in [[Taimali, Taitung|Taimali]], Taiwan which have been holding medical outreach free clinics in the area since 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/china-taiwan-province/tzu-chi-s-medical-care-survivors-after-typhoon-nepartak-taiwan|title=Tzu Chi's medical care for the survivors after Typhoon Nepartak in Taiwan|date=2016-08-24|work=ReliefWeb|access-date=2017-04-29|language=English|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825170213/http://reliefweb.int/report/china-taiwan-province/tzu-chi-s-medical-care-survivors-after-typhoon-nepartak-taiwan|archive-date=25 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1396:tzu-chi-begins-relief-work-in-southeast-taiwan-after-typhoon&catid=1:taiwan&Itemid=263&lang=en|title=Tzu Chi Begins Relief Work in Southeast Taiwan After Typhoon|work=Tzu Chi Foundation|access-date=2017-04-29|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206100816/http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1396%3Atzu-chi-begins-relief-work-in-southeast-taiwan-after-typhoon&catid=1%3Ataiwan&Itemid=263&lang=en|archive-date=6 February 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== International Disaster Relief ===\nTzu Chi has participated in numerous other relief projects around the world, including sending teams to [[Indonesia]] and [[Sri Lanka]] in the wake of the [[tsunami]] resulting from the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake]] as well as to [[Pakistan]] after the [[2005 Kashmir earthquake|2005 earthquake]] in their northern mountains.  The later was done despite poor relations between the governments of the two countries.\n\nIn the aftermath of [[Hurricane Sandy]], the organization announced on 18 November 2012 a donation of $10 million in the form of $300 and $600 [[Visa Inc.|Visa]] debit cards to those affected in the [[New York (state)|New York]] and New Jersey area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qgazette.com/news/2012-11-28/Front_Page/Liu_Announces_Buddhist_Tzu_Chi_Donation_Of_10_Mill.html|title=Liu, Announces Buddhist Tzu Chi Donation Of $10 Million|date=28 November 2012|publisher=[[The Queens Gazette]]|accessdate=4 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209064352/http://www.qgazette.com/news/2012-11-28/Front_Page/Liu_Announces_Buddhist_Tzu_Chi_Donation_Of_10_Mill.html|archive-date=9 December 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Volunteers handed out these cards in parts of [[Brooklyn]], [[Queens]], and [[Staten Island]]. Tzu Chi was also active in providing aid following the [[April 2015 Nepal earthquake|2015 Nepal Earthquake]]. Tzu Chi was also active in relief efforts during [[Hurricane Harvey]] in 2017, the group provided aid, as well as cash gifts for those who helped the community during the disaster.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://abc13.com/buddhists-come-to-aid-of-officers-hit-by-harvey/2433855/|title=Buddhists come to aid of officers hit by Harvey|last=Carson|first=Ilona|date=2017-09-20|work=ABC13 Houston|access-date=2017-10-05|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005100945/http://abc13.com/buddhists-come-to-aid-of-officers-hit-by-harvey/2433855/|archive-date=5 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local/hurricane-relief-effort/Op6XVN0u36UWqUgShrE8YP/|title=Hurricane relief effort|last=Broady|first=Arlinda|website=ajc|access-date=2017-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005154535/http://www.ajc.com/news/local/hurricane-relief-effort/Op6XVN0u36UWqUgShrE8YP/|archive-date=5 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2017/09/15/appreciation-frustration-harvey-evacuees-dallas/|title=Appreciation Turns To Frustration For Some Harvey Evacuees In Dallas|access-date=2017-10-05|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005151229/http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2017/09/15/appreciation-frustration-harvey-evacuees-dallas/|archive-date=5 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2016, the organization distributed in the United States over $2 million in cash cards to disaster victims.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lionsroar.com/buddhist-organization-tzu-chi-distributing-humanitarian-relief-in-houston-after-hurricane-harvey/|title=Buddhist organization Tzu Chi distributing humanitarian relief in Houston after Hurricane Harvey|date=2017-09-01|work=Lion's Roar|access-date=2017-09-04|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904111803/https://www.lionsroar.com/buddhist-organization-tzu-chi-distributing-humanitarian-relief-in-houston-after-hurricane-harvey/|archive-date=4 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of 2015, Tzu Chi has provided disaster relief aid to over 85 countries worldwide.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5BaMBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=tzu+chi+disaster+relief#v=onepage&q=85%20countries&f=false|title=Taiwan's Marginalized Role in International Security: Paying a Price|last=Glaser|first=Bonnie S.|last2=Vitello|first2=Jacqueline A.|date=2015-01-21|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781442240605|location=|pages=28|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Global presence==\nTzu Chi's headquarters is in [[Hualien County]], Taiwan.\n<gallery>\nFile:Jing Si Abode.jpg|Jing Si Abode (\u9759\u601d\u7cbe\u820d) of Tzu Chi Foundation\nFile:Tzu Chi Foundation Facade, Hualien (3990381753).jpg|The Hall of Still Thoughts. The Tzu Chi General Hospital is on the right\nFile:Tzu Chi Foundation (Hong Kong).jpg|Tzu-Chi Foundation in Hong Kong\nFile:The usual set up for the Tzu Chi 3-in-1 Celebration (\u6d74\u4f5b\u5178\u79ae).jpg|The usual set up for the Tzu Chi 3-in-1 Celebration (\u6d74\u4f5b\u5178\u79ae)\nFile:Tzu Chi Culture and Communication Foundation 20160607b.jpg|Tzu Chi Culture and Communication building\n</gallery>\n\n===Portfolios===\n\nTzu Chi's portfolios include case management, medical, educational and [[disaster relief]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Tzu Chi Foundation Finds Good Karma in Disaster Relief and Preparedness|url=https://www.nyredcross.org/?nd=news_room_detail&news_id=53&jid=63915|publisher=[[American Red Cross]]|accessdate=14 October 2012|date=23 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121228094810/https://www.nyredcross.org/?nd=news_room_detail&news_id=53&jid=63915|archivedate=28 December 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe organization builds and operates many hospitals and schools, with outreach efforts that range from visits to nursing homes to providing bone marrow surgery, as well as offering items such as washing machines to struggling single mothers. The television \"Da Ai\" network operates with its own news and television programming. Chinese schools have also been established abroad, such as in Australia and the United States, which apart from teaching Chinese and [[sign language]] also guides students in ways of compassion and [[community service]].\n[[File:US Navy 100226-N-6214F-040 Members of the Bouddhiste Tzu Chi Foundation, a Buddist charity based in Taiwan, distribute about 2,000 blankets and tarps to Haitian citizens.jpg|thumb|Tzu Chi volunteers distribute blankets to victims of the [[2010 Haiti earthquake|2010 Haitian Earthquake]]]]\n\n===Recycling===\n\nA significant fraction of funds raised by Tzu Chi revolves around [[environmentally friendly]] goals in encouraging the recycling of items such as water bottles as well as using reusable items or reusing items to reduce waste.\n\nAs of 2014, the foundation operates over 5,600 recycling stations.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-taiwan-recycling-20141117-story.html|title=Taiwan Buddhists transform plastic waste|last=Jennings|first=Ralph|date=17 Nov 2014|website=latimes.com|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116175356/http://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-taiwan-recycling-20141117-story.html|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> One of the foundation's projects is the recycling of [[polyethylene terephthalate]] (PET) plastic bottles for the production of textiles. The project, which was started in 2006, collects PET plastic bottles and recycles them into cloth.<ref>Tzu Chi Quarterly, Winter 2008</ref> The project is handled by the Tzu Chi sponsored non-profit Da Ai Technology Co. The products are all designed by members of the paid staff and recycled plastic bottles make up about half of the raw materials for the products. The project collects about 2,000 tons of plastic bottles each year.<ref name=\":2\" /> Tzu Chi's recycling centers have been a source of criticism however, with critics arguing that Tzu Chi's recycling efforts result in lost income for poor trash collectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2014/04/23/2003588703|title=Tzu Chi said to steal from poor - Taipei Times|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, the foundation has produced over 460,000 polyester blankets out of recycled plastic bottles, many of which have been distributed as part of Tzu Chi's disaster relief programs throughout the world. Other items made with the recycled resins include thermal underwear, T-shirts, hospital bed sheets, medical gowns, suitcases, stuffed animals and uniforms for Tzu Chi volunteers. While the project relies on recycled plastic bottles for the production of its products, its leaders have stated that it is still best for people to not use plastic bottles at all.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=300:a-greener-blanket&catid=59:internationalrelief&Itemid=183&lang=en|title=A Greener Blanket|last=Foundation|first=Tzu Chi|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927052415/http://www.tw.tzuchi.org/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=300:a-greener-blanket&catid=59:internationalrelief&Itemid=183&lang=en|archive-date=27 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://phys.org/news/2013-03-taiwan-plastic-junk-blankets-dolls.html|title=Taiwan turns plastic junk into blankets, dolls|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116183046/https://phys.org/news/2013-03-taiwan-plastic-junk-blankets-dolls.html|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n[[File:Tzu Chi Foundation in Hualien (3991128820).jpg|thumb|Inside the main hall of Tzu Chi Foundation]]\n\n===Dharma===\n\nThe teachings of the [[Buddha]] and founder Master Cheng Yen play a core role in the workings of the organization. \"Tzu Chi Day\" is celebrated every year on the second Sunday of May which generally coincides with the Buddha's birthday ([[Vesak Day]]), and [[Mother's Day]] (as recognised in Taiwan). Celebrations during Tzu Chi Day include the bathing of the Buddha ceremony, the tradition's message is that it is the people that need cleansing before they become better individuals. Tzu Chi promotes many of the teachings of Buddhism, in particular the [[Lotus Sutra]], \nand also has sutra adaptations through the use of sign language on the [[Innumerable Meanings Sutra|Sutra of the Innumerable Meanings]], which teaches that sentient existence is challenging and filled with disasters in the absence of observations of [[\u015a\u012bla|virtue]], as well as the [[Water Repentence|Sutra of the Water Repentance]], which advocates and symbolizes the need to repent [[karma|karmic transgressions]]. Despite these activities, Tzu Chi has a policy of not proselytizing religion directly at its public activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/visit-to-the-tzu-chi-foundation-in-taiwan/238309/|title=Visit to the Tzu Chi Foundation in Taiwan - The Manila Times Online|website=www.manilatimes.net|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906092112/http://www.manilatimes.net/visit-to-the-tzu-chi-foundation-in-taiwan/238309/|archive-date=6 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/114046/tzu-chi-foundation-lets-hear-it-for-amazing-buddhist-responders|title=Tzu Chi Foundation: Let's hear it for amazing Buddhist responders|last=Petilla|first=Danny|website=globalnation.inquirer.net|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116182921/https://globalnation.inquirer.net/114046/tzu-chi-foundation-lets-hear-it-for-amazing-buddhist-responders|archive-date=16 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Apart from being non-proselytist, Tzu Chi's adaptation of Buddhist principles is [[apolitical]].\n\nIn disaster regions where a particular religious faith is prominent, Tzu Chi regularly works together with local religious organizations. Tzu Chi has re-built [[mosques]] and [[church (building)|churches]] in disaster zones where faith plays an important role in local society.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzdyNvcRTWk|title=Master Cheng Yen and Tzu Chi|publisher=The Discovery Channel|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110210357/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzdyNvcRTWk|archive-date=10 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTzu Chi nuns ([[bhikkhuni]]s) do not rely on donations for their livelihood, something uncommon among most Buddhist orders. In earlier days, the nuns sustained themselves by farming, weaving and other handicrafts. More recently, they sustained themselves by the manufacture of electrical circuit breakers and other products.\n\n===International branches===\n\nTzu Chi has branches in 47 countries and regions including USA, Canada, Australia, [[Thailand]], [[Indonesia]], Malaysia, [[Singapore]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Tzu Chi Singapore|url=https://zh-tw.facebook.com/tzuchisingapore|website=Facebook|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref> and various locations in Asia, Europe and Africa.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tzuchi.org/global/offices/index.html | title=Tzu Chi Local Chapters and Associations | publisher=Buddhist Compassion Relief Tzu Chi Foundation | accessdate=29 December 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404090834/http://www.tzuchi.org/GLOBAL/offices/index.html | archivedate=4 April 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n[[File:Da Ai building of Tzu Chi University.JPG|thumb|Building for Tzu Chi's Buddhist Satellite station, Da Ai Television]]\n\n===Television and Satellite Network===\n\nOn 17 August 1999, a television network was formed in Taiwan under the Tzu Chi Foundation of the Culture of Communication, Inc with the slogan \"Love to make the world light up\". Formally known as [[Da Ai Television]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Da Ai Television|url=http://www.daai.tv/daai-web/main/|publisher=Tzu Chi Culture and Communication Foundation|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020103914/http://www.daai.tv/daai-web/main/|archive-date=20 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the network grew into a global broadcasting presence with offerings of a radio service,<ref>{{cite web|title=radio.newdaai.tv|url=http://radio.newdaai.tv/aod/index_in.php|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910195337/http://radio.newdaai.tv/aod/index_in.php|archive-date=10 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tzu Chi Channel 1, Tzu Chi Channel 2, Da Ai TV Indonesia, Da Ai TV Thailand, and Da Ai TV Egypt. Live streaming of Channel 1 and 2 can also be found on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u5927\u611b\u96fb\u8996\u4e00\u81fa Live \u76f4\u64ad|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ukWk-Gy0NT8|website=Youtube|publisher=Tzu Chi DaAiVideo|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220132054/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ukWk-Gy0NT8|archive-date=20 December 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Jing Si Books & Caf\u00e9===\n\nJing Si Books & Caf\u00e9 is a chain of non-profit bookstores and cafes operated by Tzu Chi offering Tzu Chi merchandise and publications by [[Cheng Yen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jing Si Books & Cafe|url=http://jingsi.com.tw/|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911002133/http://jingsi.com.tw/|archive-date=11 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Youth==\n\nThe Tzu Chi Collegiate Association (\u6148\u6fdf\u5927\u5c08\u9752\u5e74\u806f\u8abc\u6703) is the Foundation's college youth organization,<ref>{{cite web|title=Tzu Chi Collegiate Association (Singapore)|url=http://sgtzuching2014en.wordpress.com|website=\u6148\u6fdf\u5927\u5c08\u9752\u5e74\u806f\u8abc\u6703\uff08\u65b0\u52a0\u5761\uff09|publisher=WordPress.com|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910195926/http://sgtzuching2014en.wordpress.com/|archive-date=10 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and was officially established in Taiwan on 31 May 1992. With chapters at universities worldwide, its goal is to allow university students (known as Tzu Ching or \u6148\u9752, literally \"compassionate youth\") to be involved with Tzu Chi's activities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore Tzu Ching \u65b0\u52a0\u5761\u6148\u9752|url=http://sgtzuching3in1.blogspot.sg|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911001701/http://sgtzuching3in1.blogspot.sg/|archive-date=11 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=What is Tzu Ching|url=http://www.umich.edu/~tzuching/|work=Tzu Chi Collegiate Association at the University of Michigan|publisher=[[University of Michigan]]|accessdate=22 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222213236/http://www.umich.edu/~tzuching/|archive-date=22 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tzu Ching volunteers are given the opportunity to participate in large-scale events such as disaster relief and international NGO conferences such as the annual [[UN Youth Assembly]]. Master Cheng Yen encourages the Tzu Ching volunteers to actively communicate with each other, with the goals of learning and improving. Each year an international Tzu Ching officer training retreat camp is held at the foundation headquarters in [[Hualien City|Hualien]].\n\nTzu Shao (\u6148\u5c11) is the Tzu Chi branch for youths under the age of 18. People in this group do community services such as free clinics, soup kitchens, and nursery homes.\n\n==Year End Ceremonies==\n\nEach year Tzu Chi conducts a Year End Ceremony attended by Tzu Chi workers, volunteers and members in January or February where Master [[Cheng Yen]] distributes blessings in the form of red packets that embosses a coin in Taiwanese currency{{Refn|The coin symbolizes the fifty cents the thirty housewives saved at the founding of Tzu Chi|group=note}} together with auspicious words for the coming year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tzu Chi Year End Ceremony 2013|url=http://yeb.tzuchi.org.sg|accessdate=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910200034/http://yeb.tzuchi.org.sg/|archive-date=10 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=note|20em}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Yu-Shuang Yao|title=Taiwan's Tzu Chi as Engaged Buddhism: Origins, Organization, Appeal and Social Impact|url=|date=2012|publisher=Global Oriental|isbn=978-90-04-21747-8}}\n* Gombrich, Richard (2013). [https://www.uni-marburg.de/fb03/ivk/mjr/pdfs/2013/reviews/rev_gombrich_2013.pdf Review: Yu-Shuang Yao, Taiwan's Tzu Chi as Engaged Buddhism: Origins, Organization, Appeal and Social Impact, Global Oriental 2012]. Marburg Journal of Religion 17 (1), 1-8\n* {{cite book|author=C. Julia Huang|title=Charisma and Compassion: Cheng Yen and the Buddhist Tzu Chi Movement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t529SPeue5MC|year=2009|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-03133-3}}\n* Jones, Charles B. (2009). [http://www.globalbuddhism.org/jgb/index.php/jgb/article/view/99/113 Modernization and Traditionalism in Buddhist Almsgiving: The Case of the Buddhist Compassion Relief Tzu-chi Association in Taiwan]. Journal of Global Buddhism 10, 291-319\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://tw.tzuchi.org/en/ Official Site (Global Homepage)]\n*[http://www.tzuchi.us/ Official Site (USA)]\n*[http://www.books.com.tw/exep/assp.php/jamezku/products/F012089631 TzuChi, Serving with Compassion (English Guideline)]\n\n{{Commons category|Tzu Chi}}\n{{Four Great Mountains}}\n\n[[Category:Tzu Chi| ]]\n[[Category:Buddhist organizations based in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:International charities]]\n[[Category:International volunteer organizations]]\n[[Category:Religious service organizations]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1966]]\n", "name_user": "Mistakefinder", "label": "safe", "comment": "add link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tzu_Chi"}
{"title_page": "John Scurr", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:John Scurr.gif|thumb|right|Scurr in 1914]]\n'''John Scurr''' (6 April 1876 \u2013 10 July 1932), born '''John Rennie''', was an [[England|English]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician and [[trade union]] official who served as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Mile End (UK Parliament constituency)|Mile End]] from 1923 to 1931.\n\nScurr was born in [[Brisbane]], [[Australia]], the son of Louis James Rennie, an immigrant from [[London]], but was adopted by his uncle, Captain John Scurr, and brought to London at six months old. He spent his life in [[Poplar, London|Poplar]] in the [[East End]], from which his family came, a lifelong supporter of [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] and Labour causes.  In 1900, he married an Irish woman named [[Julia Scurr|Julia Sullivan]], who became a prominent politician and campaigner for women's rights,<ref name=\"odnb\">\"[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/articleHL/77194 Poplar councillors]\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''</ref> who led a deputation (on behalf of Sylvia Pankhurst) to meet Prime Minister [[H. H. Asquith|Asquith]],  in 1914 and pleaded for suffrage for women supported by the poor working-class men and women of East London .<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Rise up, women! : the remarkable lives of the suffragettes|last=Diane|first=Atkinson|publisher=Bloomsbury|year=2018|isbn=9781408844045|location=London|pages=503|oclc=1016848621}}</ref> They had two sons and a daughter born within four years. She died in 1927.\n\nHe was an accountant<ref name=\":0\" /> and active member of Poplar [[Trades Council]] (and later served as its president) and was elected as an [[alderman]] to [[Poplar Borough Council]] in 1919. He served as [[mayor]] in 1922\u20131923, vice-chairman (1920\u20131922) and chairman (1922\u20131923) of the Metropolitan Boroughs Standing Joint Committee, and an alderman of [[London County Council]] from 1925 to 1929. In 1921, he was imprisoned, along with 29 other Poplar councillors, as a protest against unequal [[rates (tax)|rates]].\n\nIn 1913, when Scurr was Chairman of the London District Committee of the [[Dock, Wharf, Riverside and General Labourers' Union]], he was a last minute socialist candidate at the [[1913 Chesterfield by-election|Chesterfield by-election]]. \n{{Election box begin |\n  |title=[[1913 Chesterfield by-election]]\nElectorate 16,995}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Barnet Kenyon]]\n  |votes      = 7,725\n  |percentage =55.8\n  |change     =\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Edward Christie\n  |votes      = 5,539\n  |percentage =40.0\n  |change     =\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Independent Labour\n  |candidate  = John Scurr\n  |votes      = 583\n  |percentage =4.2\n  |change     =\n  }}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      = \n  |percentage = 81.5\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 2,186\n  |percentage = 15.8\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n  |winner     = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |loser     = Labour Party (UK)\n  |swing      =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nHe contested the [[1914 Ipswich by-election]], where he finished in third place; as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] gained the seat from the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberals]].\n\nAt the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]], he unsuccessfully contested the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] seat of [[Buckingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckingham]], splitting the anti-Tory vote and allowing the Conservatives to win. He was defeated again at the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]] in the Mile End constituency in the East End.\n\nScurr won the Mile End seat at the [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923 general election]], unseating the Conservative MP [[Walter Preston (UK politician)|Sir Walter Preston]]. He was re-elected in [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]] and [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]], but lost his seat when the Labour Party split at the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 general election]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book |last=Craig |first=F. W. S. |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig  |title=British parliamentary election results 1918-1949 |origyear=1969 |edition= 3rd |year=1983 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-06-X}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*Obituary, ''[[The Times]]'', 11 July 1932\n*''[[Who Was Who]]''\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-john-scurr | John Scurr }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Mile End (UK Parliament constituency)|Mile End]]\n  | years  = [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]]\u2013[[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931]]\n  | before = Sir [[Walter Preston (UK politician)|Walter Preston]]\n  | after  = [[William O'Donovan (politician)|William O'Donovan]]\n}}\n{{s-civic}}\n{{succession box|title=Mayor of Poplar|years=1922\u20131923|before=[[Charlie Sumner (politician)|Charlie Sumner]]|after=[[Charles Key]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=London Division representative on the [[Independent Labour Party]] National Administrative Council|years=1926\u20131927|before=[[Ernest E. Hunter]]|after=[[Ernest E. Hunter]]}}\n{{succession box|title=London Division representative on the [[Independent Labour Party]] National Administrative Council|years=1928\u20131929|before=[[Ernest E. Hunter]]|after=[[J. Allen Skinner]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scurr, John}}\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Brisbane]]\n[[Category:People from Poplar, London]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Independent Labour Party National Administrative Committee members]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from London]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:Members of Poplar Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Greater London]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:John Scurr.gif|thumb|right|Scurr in 1914]]\n'''John Scurr''' (6 April 1876 \u2013 10 July 1932), born '''John Rennie''', was an [[England|English]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician and [[trade union]] official who served as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Mile End (UK Parliament constituency)|Mile End]] from 1923 to 1931.\n\nScurr was born in [[Brisbane]], [[Australia]], the son of Louis James Rennie, an immigrant from [[London]], but was adopted by his uncle, Captain John Scurr, and brought to London at six months old. He spent his life in [[Poplar, London|Poplar]] in the [[East End]], from which his family came, a lifelong supporter of [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] and Labour causes.  In 1900, he married an Irish woman named [[Julia Scurr|Julia Sullivan]], who became a prominent politician and campaigner for women's rights,<ref name=\"odnb\">\"[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/articleHL/77194 Poplar councillors]\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''</ref> who led a deputation (on behalf of Sylvia Pankhurst) to meet Prime Minister [[H. H. Asquith|Asquith]],  in 1914 and pleaded for suffrage for women supported by the poor working-class men and women of East London .<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Rise up, women! : the remarkable lives of the suffragettes|last=Diane|first=Atkinson|publisher=Bloomsbury|year=2018|isbn=9781408844045|location=London|pages=503|oclc=1016848621}}</ref> They had two sons and a daughter born within four years. She died in 1927.\n\nHe was an accountant<ref name=\":0\" /> and active member of Poplar [[Trades Council]] (and later served as its president) and was elected as an [[alderman]] to [[Poplar Borough Council]] in 1919. He served as [[mayor]] in 1922\u20131923, vice-chairman (1920\u20131922) and chairman (1922\u20131923) of the Metropolitan Boroughs Standing Joint Committee, and an alderman of [[London County Council]] from 1925\u201329. In 1921, he was imprisoned, along with 29 other Poplar councillors, as a protest against unequal [[rates (tax)|rates]].\n\nIn 1913, when Scurr was Chairman of the London District Committee of the [[Dock, Wharf, Riverside and General Labourers' Union]], he was a last minute socialist candidate at the [[1913 Chesterfield by-election|Chesterfield by-election]]. \n{{Election box begin |\n  |title=[[1913 Chesterfield by-election]]\nElectorate 16,995}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Barnet Kenyon]]\n  |votes      = 7,725\n  |percentage =55.8\n  |change     =\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Edward Christie\n  |votes      = 5,539\n  |percentage =40.0\n  |change     =\n }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Independent Labour\n  |candidate  = John Scurr\n  |votes      = 583\n  |percentage =4.2\n  |change     =\n  }}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      = \n  |percentage = 81.5\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 2,186\n  |percentage = 15.8\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n  |winner     = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |loser     = Labour Party (UK)\n  |swing      =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nHe contested the [[1914 Ipswich by-election]], where he finished in third place; as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] gained the seat from the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberals]].\n\nAt the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]], he unsuccessfully contested the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] seat of [[Buckingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckingham]], splitting the anti-Tory vote and allowing the Conservatives to win. He was defeated again at the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]] in the Mile End constituency in the East End.\n\nScurr won the Mile End seat at the [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923 general election]], unseating the Conservative MP [[Walter Preston (UK politician)|Sir Walter Preston]]. He was re-elected in [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]] and [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]], but lost his seat when the Labour Party split at the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 general election]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book |last=Craig |first=F. W. S. |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig  |title=British parliamentary election results 1918-1949 |origyear=1969 |edition= 3rd |year=1983 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-06-X}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*Obituary, ''[[The Times]]'', 11 July 1932\n*''[[Who Was Who]]''\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-john-scurr | John Scurr }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Mile End (UK Parliament constituency)|Mile End]]\n  | years  = [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]]\u2013[[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931]]\n  | before = Sir [[Walter Preston (UK politician)|Walter Preston]]\n  | after  = [[William O'Donovan (politician)|William O'Donovan]]\n}}\n{{s-civic}}\n{{succession box|title=Mayor of Poplar|years=1922\u20131923|before=[[Charlie Sumner (politician)|Charlie Sumner]]|after=[[Charles Key]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=London Division representative on the [[Independent Labour Party]] National Administrative Council|years=1926\u20131927|before=[[Ernest E. Hunter]]|after=[[Ernest E. Hunter]]}}\n{{succession box|title=London Division representative on the [[Independent Labour Party]] National Administrative Council|years=1928\u20131929|before=[[Ernest E. Hunter]]|after=[[J. Allen Skinner]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scurr, John}}\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Brisbane]]\n[[Category:People from Poplar, London]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Independent Labour Party National Administrative Committee members]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from London]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:Members of Poplar Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Greater London]]\n", "name_user": "Necrothesp", "label": "safe", "comment": "much better", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Scurr"}
{"title_page": "Dorsey Armstrong", "text_new": "'''Dorsey Armstrong''' (born 1970) is Professor of English and Medieval Literature at [[Purdue University]]. She received her Ph.D. in [[Medieval Literature]] from [[Duke University]] in 1998 and her BA in English and Creative Writing from Stanford University<ref>[https://cla.purdue.edu/facultyStaff/profiles/promoted/promotions-15/Armstrong._Dorsey.html Dorsey Armstrong, Purdue University College of Liberal Arts]</ref>. Before joining the English department at Purdue in 2002, she taught at [[Centenary College of Louisiana]] and [[California State University, Long Beach]]. Her research interests include medieval women writers; late medieval print culture; and the [[King Arthur|Arthurian legend]].\n\n==Works==\nHer book ''Gender and the Chivalric Community in Sir Thomas Malory\u2019s \u201cMorte d\u2019Arthur\u201d '' was published by [[University Press of Florida]] in 2003,<ref>{{ISBN|978-0-8130-2686-2}}</ref> and widely reviewed.<ref>Review, ''[[The Modern Language Review]]'', April 2005, vol. 100, no. 2, pp. 477\u201379 [http://www.worldcat.org/title/review-of-gender-and-the-chivalric-community-in-malorys-morte-darthur/oclc/480653264&referer=brief_results]</ref><ref>''[[The Journal of English and Germanic Philology]]'' Oct 2005 v104 i4 p. 570(3)</ref><ref>''[[Speculum: A Journal of Medieval Studies]]'' Oct 2005 v80 i4 pp. 1229\u201331</ref><ref>'' [[CHOICE: Current Reviews for Academic Libraries]]'' May 2004 v41 i9 p. 1660(2)</ref> \u00a0\nHer translation of [[Sir Thomas Malory]]\u2019s ''Morte Darthur : A Modern English Translation'', was published by [[Parlor Press]] in 2009,<ref>{{ISBN|978-1-60235-103-5}}</ref> has been reviewed \u00a0<ref>''Reference & Research Book News'' (November 1, 2009 ; {{ISBN|1-60235-103-1}} )</ref> \u00a0 and is held in over 4500 WorldCat libraries <ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/sir-thomas-malorys-morte-darthur-a-new-modern-english-translation-based-on-the-winchester-manuscript/oclc/405107550&referer=brief_results]</ref>  She became editor in chief of the academic journal ''[[Arthuriana]]'' in January 2009. Armstrong's work ''Mapping Malory: Regional Identities and National Geographies in Le Morte Darthur'', written in collaboration with Kenneth Hodges, explores the role played by geography in Malory's works. Armstrong has won numerous awards for rigorous and engaged teaching style. She has taped six lecture series for [[The Teaching Company]], five of them on the medieval world and another on writing.<ref>http://www.thegreatcourses.com/tgc/professors/professor_detail.aspx?pid=381</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.cla.purdue.edu/facultystaff/profiles/promoted/promotions-15/Armstrong._Dorsey.html Biography on Purdue website]\n*{{worldcat id|id=lccn-n2003-52654|name=Armstrong, Dorsey 1970- }}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Armstrong, Dorsey}}\n[[Category:American literary critics]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Purdue University faculty]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Arthurian scholars]]\n", "text_old": "'''Dorsey Armstrong''' (born 1970) is Professor of English and Medieval Literature at [[Purdue University]]. She received her Ph.D. in [[Medieval Literature]] from [[Duke University]] in 1998 and her BA in English and Creative Writing from Stanford University<ref>[https://cla.purdue.edu/facultyStaff/profiles/promoted/promotions-15/Armstrong._Dorsey.html Dorsey Armstrong, Purdue University College of Liberal Arts]</ref>. Before joining the English department at Purdue in 2002, she taught at [[Centenary College of Louisiana]] and [[California State University, Long Beach]]. Her research interests include medieval women writers; late medieval print culture; and the [[King Arthur|Arthurian legend]].\n\n==Works==\nHer book ''Gender and the Chivalric Community in Sir Thomas Malory\u2019s \u201cMorte d\u2019Arthur\u201d '' was published by [[University Press of Florida]] in 2003,<ref>{{ISBN|978-0-8130-2686-2}}</ref> \u00a0 \u00a0 and widely reviewed.<ref>Review, ''[[The Modern Language Review]]'', Apr., 2005, vol. 100, no. 2, pp. 477\u201379 [http://www.worldcat.org/title/review-of-gender-and-the-chivalric-community-in-malorys-morte-darthur/oclc/480653264&referer=brief_results]</ref><ref>''[[The Journal of English and Germanic Philology]]'' Oct 2005 v104 i4 p. 570(3)</ref><ref>''[[Speculum: A Journal of Medieval Studies]]'' Oct 2005 v80 i4 pp. 1229\u201331</ref><ref>'' [[CHOICE: Current Reviews for Academic Libraries]]'' May 2004 v41 i9 p. 1660(2)</ref> \u00a0\nHer translation of [[Sir Thomas Malory]]\u2019s ''Morte Darthur : A Modern English Translation'', was published by [[Parlor Press]] in 2009,<ref>{{ISBN|978-1-60235-103-5}}</ref> has been reviewed \u00a0<ref>''Reference & Research Book News'' (November 1, 2009 ; {{ISBN|1-60235-103-1}} )</ref> \u00a0 and is held in over 4500 WorldCat libraries <ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/sir-thomas-malorys-morte-darthur-a-new-modern-english-translation-based-on-the-winchester-manuscript/oclc/405107550&referer=brief_results]</ref>  She became editor in chief of the academic journal ''[[Arthuriana]]'' in January 2009. Armstrong's work ''Mapping Malory: Regional Identities and National Geographies in Le Morte Darthur'', written in collaboration with Kenneth Hodges, explores the role played by geography in Malory's works. Armstrong has won numerous awards for rigorous and engaged teaching style. She has taped six lecture series for [[The Teaching Company]], five of them on the medieval world and another on writing.<ref>http://www.thegreatcourses.com/tgc/professors/professor_detail.aspx?pid=381</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.cla.purdue.edu/facultystaff/profiles/promoted/promotions-15/Armstrong._Dorsey.html Biography on Purdue website]\n*{{worldcat id|id=lccn-n2003-52654|name=Armstrong, Dorsey 1970- }}\n\n{{authority control}